<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-India     04-23 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-India,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Says Bofors Bribed Indian Family for Weapons Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish radio said Friday it had
obtained documents supporting allegations that a family of Indian
financiers received $13.7 million in connection with a Swedish arms
sale to India.
   It said the documents included telex messages between the
Swedish firm AB Bofors and two Swiss banks in Geneva in 1986
dealing with accounts under the control of London-based members of
the Hinduja family.
   In New Delhi, the newspaper Hindu also reported the allegations.
   G. P. Hinduja, one of four brothers active in the family
operations, called the information ``a complete fabrication'' in a
statement to the Hindu. Bofors spokesman Per Mossberg was quoted as
denying the allegations.
   The telex messages indicated the account holder was promised a
10 percent commission on a $1.4 billion Indian contract for 155mm
howitzers made by Bofors, Sweden's largest arms manufacturer, the
Swedish radio said.
   It described the Hindujas as being close to Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi and his Congress Party.
   The broadcast said money from Bofors passed through accounts
held by the Hinduja family at the British Bank of the Middle East
and the Continental Illinois Bank in Geneva. It claimed the
deposits were transferred to Sangam Ltd. in London, a company
Swedish radio said was owned by the Hinduja family.
   Gandhi's government was facing allegations of corruption when it
negotiated the deal with Bofors in 1986 and made the condition that
no middlemen be used. A Swedish investigation last June found that
Bofors paid up to $40 million to individuals, but the company
legally blocked access to further information.
   In New Delhi, a Parliament committee dealing with the case
adopted its final report Friday, but the United News of India said
investigators had ``drawn a blank.''
   The report was not made public. It is to be presented to
Parliament next Friday.
   Gandhi pledged anew that the government would punish any Indian
who profited from the deal illegally, UNI said. He was in Madras
for a two-day Congress Party meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
