<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Reagan Bjt   04-23 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Reagan, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Meese Should Stay In Office, Helps Fill Key Vacancy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is moving to fill one Justice
Department slot and Attorney General Edwin Meese III is appointing
temporary replacements for up to a dozen others in an attempt to
end the turmoil caused by the March 29 protest resignations of two
key Meese aides.
   Reagan on Friday moved quickly to ease Meese's personnel
problems by nominating Francis Keating to fill the associate
attorney general's slot, the department's empty No. 3 post.
   Reagan also said Meese should stay in office and the Justice
Department is running ``just fine,'' although two top Meese aides
who quit told Reagan on Wednesday a ``deep malaise'' had
``infected'' the department and one of them said Meese should be
indicted.
   Keating would replace Stephen Trott, who left the department a
week ago to become a federal judge. His was not one of the protest
resignations, but the vacancy has been affected by the concern with
Meese's leadership.
   Keating, an assistant Treasury secretary, may come in to the
Justice Department on an acting basis late next week until he can
be confirmed by the Senate.
   The Nos. 2 and 3 offices at the Justice Department are virtually
vacant from the top down, and the department plans to shore them up
by naming perhaps nearly a dozen people in all, department
spokesman Patrick Korten said. The posts probably will be filled on
Monday.
   Korten added, ``Meese absolutely has no intention of stepping
down.''
   An independent counsel has been examining Meese's assistance to
scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and a proposed $1 billion Iraqi oil
pipeline project at the behest of longtime friend E. Robert
Wallach. Also under investigation are Meese's meetings with
regional Bell telephone company executives at a time when he owned
$14,000 in Baby Bell stock and Wallach's role in securing a
$40,000-a-year job for Meese's wife.
   Since the protest resignations of Deputy Attorney General Arnold
Burns and Assistant Attorney General William Weld, Meese has twice
unsuccessfully tried to fill Burns' post.
   Philadelphia lawyer Arlin Adams rejected Meese's overtures, and
at least five current or former U.S. attorneys who have been
sounded out about Weld's job have said they weren't interested. St.
Louis attorney John Shepherd withdrew from consideration for Burns'
post Wednesday after adverse publicity about an alleged affair with
his law firm's bookkeeper and other matters.
   Weld was ``unequivocal'' at the White House meeting in telling
the president that if it were up to him, he would seek an
indictment of Meese, said an administration source who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The former criminal division chief then proceeded to lay out
``an oral indictment'' of Meese to the president, said the source,
focusing on Meese's relationship with Wallach.
   Wallach is under indictment in the Wedtech scandal.
   The administration source said Burns told the president that
Meese had violated the standards of ethical conduct for executive
branch employees spelled out in a 1965 executive order.
   Burns, according to the source, said that in other similar
instances of possible impropriety, Justice Department lawyers would
be placed on administrative leave, disciplined or dismissed.
   ``The president was very attentive,'' said the source, adding
that ``it was clear he was hearing for the first time that not
everything is well in Denmark.''
   The ethical standards say employees should avoid any action
which could create the appearance of using public office for
private gain, giving preferential treatment to any organization or
person or making a government decision outside official channels.
   Vice President George Bush, Baker and White House counsel A.B.
Culvahouse also attended the meeting.
   Meese was summoned to a 40-minute meeting with Reagan
immediately afterward.
   According to Korten, the president told Meese at the end of
their meeting that he was ``satisfied and supportive'' of the
attorney general.
   Burns left his post officially on Friday, 3{ weeks after
resigning to protest Meese's continued tenure as attorney general.
   Independent counsel James C. McKay, who has been conducting a
criminal investigation of Meese since last May 11, is expected to
issue a report of Meese's activites if he doesn't seek an
indictment of the attorney general.
   It is likely the Justice Department's Office of Professional
Responsibility will then examine ethical questions raised as a
result of McKay's probe and will recommend to Reagan whether Meese
should be disciplined or fired.
</TEXT>
