<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagans-Health Bjt   04-23 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagans-Health, Bjt,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Test Shows No Recurrence Of Breast Cancer For First Lady</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mammogram of Nancy Reagan's right breast
shows no sign of cancer, the White House says.
   While the first lady went to Bethesda Naval Hospital to have her
six-month checkup following removal of her cancerous left breast,
President Reagan had dental X-rays done there.
   The first couple flew by helicopter Friday to the suburban
Maryland military facility from the White House, remained there for
less than a half-hour, then went to Camp David for the weekend.
   ``The president and first lady completed their routine
radiological procedures,'' White House physician Dr. John Hutton
said.
   ``The president had a series of routine dental X-rays in the
dental clinic, while Mrs. Reagan had her first post-operative
mammogram,'' he said. ``The mammogram was negative. No immediate
treatment of any kind is required as a result of today's procedures
on the president and first lady.''
   The White House had said earlier that the examinations were not
prompted by any current physicial problems of either of the Reagans.
   The Reagans did not answer reporters' questions when they left
the White House or on arrival or departure from the hospital.
   Reagan, however, made an ``A-OK'' thumb-and-forefinger sign,
indicating things went well.
   The last time the 77-year-old president visited the hospital was
in January, when he underwent his semi-annual checkup for colon
cancer. He has had regular checkups every January and June since he
underwent surgery for an intestinal malignancy in July 1985.
   Elaine Crispen, Mrs. Reagan's press secretary, said, ``It's wise
and routine to check the other breast'' after surgery of the kind
the first lady had six months ago.
   She said the first lady has had periodic examinations since her
operation Oct. 17, 1987, but this was her first X-ray of the right
breast.
   Mrs. Crispen said the couple wanted to have the results of Mrs.
Reagan's exam promptly ``so they could send her off for a
comfortable, worry-free weekend.''
   Mrs. Reagan, 66, had her breast removed after doctors discovered
a quarter-inch cancerous lesion. She chose to undergo a modified
radical mastectomy, which involves the removal of the entire breast
and some lymph nodes.
   Mrs. Crispen said that not only was it time for the first lady's
six-month checkup, but the president could use the time ``to get
his dental X-rays taken, rather than usually doing it at the White
House.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan usually has a
cleaning and checkup every three months at the White House, but
that the president planned to have a ``panoramic'' X-ray done this
time in order to get a full-view picture of his mouth.
   The White House has X-ray machines that take pictures of parts
of the mouth, but does not have the larger machine that pans the
entire mouth area, he said.
   Panoramic radiographs, or X-rays that provide an overall view of
the teeth and jaws, are used to diagnose problems ranging from
cavities to tumors.
</TEXT>
