<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra Bjt   04-23 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Administration Officials Called To Testify Against North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A host of current and former top government
officials are listed as prosecution witnesses for the Iran-Contra
conspiracy trial of Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L. North and three
co-defendants.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz and two top deputies and
Attorney Edwin Meese III and two of his top aides are among the
list of 105 witnesses submitted in a court filing Friday by
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh.
   The list includes national security officials knowledgeable
about the covert sale of U.S. arms to Iran, private operatives who
ran the secret supply network that armed the Nicaraguan rebels,
Contra leaders and wealthy donors who contributed to their cause.
   No date has been set for the trial of North, former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter and two arms dealers: retired
Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim.
   They are accused of conspiring to divert profits illegally from
the U.S.-Iran arms sales to help the Contras during a ban on direct
American military aid to the rebels.
   Walsh filed the witness list in advance of Monday's hearing
called by U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell to determine if
prosecutors impermissibly relied on evidence derived from the
compelled congressional testimony of North, Hakim and Poindexter.
   Most of the witnesses were known to Walsh before Hakim received
congressional immunity on April 20, 1987.
   The list includes deputy CIA director Robert Gates, former White
House chief of staff Donald Regan, former national security adviser
Robert McFarlane and assistant attorneys general William Bradford
Reynolds and Charles Cooper.
   Meese, Cooper, and Reynolds would be expected to testify about
the November 1986 investigation they conducted that uncovered the
diversion of arms-sale profits.
   The defense, meanwhile, indicated that it will call Reynolds as
a witness during the hearing on the immunity question. The defense
wants to show that statements he made to the grand jury were
influenced by the defendants' compelled congressional testimony,
according to court papers.
   Late Friday, Gesell issued an order blocking a defense attempt
to subpoena nine members of Walsh's staff to testify at the hearing.
   Seven of the prospective trial witnesses are referred to only by
number ``because of national security concerns,'' Walsh said. Their
identities were given privately to the court and the defense.
   Other top officials on the list include Assistant Secretary of
State Elliott Abrams, State Department legal adviser Abraham Sofaer
and former CIA general counsel Stanley Sporkin, now a federal judge
here.
   McFarlane, who pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of
withholding information from Congress about covert aid to the
Contras, is one of several former National Security Council
officials on the list, which includes North's former secretary Fawn
Hall.
   Contra leaders Adolfo Calero and Luis Alfonse Robelo are listed
along with retired Army Maj. Gen. John Singlaub, who helped raise
private money for the anti-Sandinista cause.
   Donors Ellen Garwood, William O'Boyle, and C. Thomas Claggett,
Jr. are listed along with William Haskell, who owned land in
Central America where an airstrip was built for resupply operations.
   Also on the list were two conservative fund-raisers, Carl R.
``Spitz'' Channell and Richard Miller. Channell and Miller pleaded
guilty last year to conspiring illegally to use a tax-exempt
foundation to help raise Contra money.
   The defense indicated it also wanted to call Secord and former
National Security Council aide Kenneth deGraffenreid as witnesses
at next week's hearing.
   Walsh's office moved to disqualify the defense from calling any
witnesses on the ground that the lawyers did not meet Thursday's
deadline for notifying the prosecution of the grand jury witness
they intended to produce at the hearing.
   The prosecutor also argued that deGraffenreid and Secord weren't
grand jury witnesses and therefore couldn't testify at next week's
hearing.
   The defense apparently wants to put Secord on the witness stand
to show that testimony he gave to Congress, without immunity, was
based on information he received from Hakim, who gave closed-door
testimony to the congressional committees before the public
hearings began last spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
