<DOCNO> AP880423-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ShroudofTurin Bjt   04-23 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shroud of Turin, Bjt,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sample Taken For Dating of Shroud Venerated As Christ's Burial
Cloth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tiny sample has been cut from the Shroud
of Turin for radiocarbon-dating that may determine whether the
cloth existed at the time of Christ's death on the cross, the
Vatican announced.
   The linen, which appears to bear the image of a crucified man,
is venerated by some as Christ's burial cloth.
   The operation, eagerly awaited by scientists, was carried out
Thursday in Turin under the supervision of Cardinal Anastasio
Ballestrero, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Turin, Italy, with
the collaboration of Dr. Michael Tite of the British Museum, the
Vatican said.
   The British Museum has agreed to guarantee the scientific
validity of the carbon-dating, which is to be done independently on
nuclear atom-counters at Oxford, the University of Arizona and the
Swiss Federal Institute of Technology at the University of Zurich.
   The Vatican, which owns the shroud, had resisted carbon-dating
on grounds it would damage the cloth, which is 14 feet, 3 inches
long and 3 feet, 7 inches wide. But the development in the 1970s of
an atom-counter known as an accelerator mass spectrometer made it
possible to date objects with much smaller samples.
   The shroud, whose history is well-documented from the mid-14th
century, has been kept in the Turin Cathedral since 1578.
   A piece of cloth measuring just 1 centimeter by 7 centimeters
(four-tenths of an inch by 2.8 inches) was cut from the shroud,
then cut further into three samples for the laboratories, Friday's
Vatican announcement said.
   The size of the individual samples was not given, but Tite has
previously said each laboratory would receive a 0.3-square-inch
sample of the shroud.
   The Vatican said the area of cutting was chosen to guarantee
that the sample belongs to the principal body of the shroud and
that the cut would cause ``the least damage possible to the cloth.''
   It said the entire operation was videotaped and photographed.
   Each laboratory will also receive two dummy cloth samples, one
carbon-dated and the other dated historically but not
scientifically to see if they get consistent results for all three
samples. The labs are not being told which sample is from the
shroud, the Vatican said.
   Tite has said the triple carbon-dating should reveal the
shroud's age within a 200-year range. The results are expected to
be announced by summer.
   The tests will not prove that the image on the cloth is
Christ's, but would indicate whether the shroud existed when Christ
was crucified.
   The shroud bears a faint yellowish image of both the front and
back of a man's body. Stains, scientifically identified as blood,
can be seen around the wrists.
   Believers contend the image was left by a supernatural burst of
energy accompanying Christ's resurrection, while skeptics claim it
was painted during the Middle Ages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880423-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KennedyFiles     04-23 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Files,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Destroyed Files Were Duplicates, Police Said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 2,500 photographs from the Robert F.
Kennedy assassination file were destroyed because they were
unneeded duplicates that took up filing space, a police spokesman
says.
   Commander Bill Booth, responding to questions about the
destruction disclosed earlier this week, said Friday the
explanation came from a retired police officer who was very
involved in the case.
   He declined to give the officer's name, saying, ``He has been
retired for some time and is disinclined to get involved.''
   But he said the man ``has an independent recollection'' of
events relating to the pictures.
   In the aftermath of Kennedy's assassination at the Ambassador
Hotel on June 5, 1968, he said, police took photographs of every
possible angle of the crime scene.
   ``What happened is there were many hundreds of photographs
taken, thousands of photographs,'' Booth said. ``And many copies of
each photograph were copied for us and for each agency involved.''
   ``What were destroyed were superfluous duplicates that amounted
to a lot of redundancy,'' he said. ``There was no need to keep
them. Filing space was a consideration.''
   The police department's voluminous file on the Kennedy
assassination was released for the first time Tuesday, and
California Archivist John Burns noted a certificate showing that
2,410 photographs were burned by police two months after Kennedy's
death.
   Police earlier had conceded they destroyed ceiling panels and
part of a door jamb from the kitchen of the Ambassador that became
central to investigation of whether a second gun might have been
fired at the New York senator.
   Sirhan Sirhan, a Jordanian immigrant, was convicted of murdering
Kennedy and is serving a life term at Soledad Prison. He has said
he was the lone assassin but insists he has no memory of the actual
shooting. He blames alcohol for his amnesia.
   In another development, the woman who told police in 1968 that
she saw a girl in a polka-dot dress run from the assassination
scene declared she had been badgered into recanting her original
story.
   The newly released police files showed that Sandra Serrano
withdrew her statement two weeks after the killing, saying, ``The
whole thing was a lie.''
   But the woman, now Sandra Serrano-Sewell, told a radio reporter
Thursday that she was a victim of police harassment.
   She had reported seeing a girl in a polka dot dress running from
the Ambassador Hotel shouting, ``We shot him. We shot him.'' When
she asked who was shot, she said the woman replied, ``Senator
Kennedy.''
   But her retraction of the story led police to cancel a search
for such a girl, the files showed.
   In an interview with KUOP Radio in Stockton, Ms. Serrano-Sewell
said, ``There was a lot of badgering that was going on. I was just
20 years old, and I became unglued. ... I said what they wanted me
to say.''
   Asked on Friday about the woman's statements, Booth said, ``Our
conclusion was she did not tell the truth when she gave all that
information. ... The files have to speak for themselves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
