<BYLINE>Names in the News</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deaf actress Marlee Matlin says she's unhappy
with the way The New York Times treated her decision to speak
without using sign language on the Academy Awards program.
   The Times' article on April 13 said some people viewed her
appearance earlier this month as ``a blow not only to deaf people
but also to the goal of `total communication.'''
   ``I do not sign and speak simultaneously, and when I chose to
sign alone (with an off-camera voice) or to speak alone, as I did
on the Oscar ceremony telecast, I could have potentially ignored
two major segments of the deaf community _ those who use speech and
do not sign and those who sign and do not use speech,'' she wrote
in a letter to the newspaper published Friday.
   ``Fortunately, the telecast was closed captioned ... and
everyone, regardless of communication preference, had access. So
what's the big fuss?'' The star of ``Children of a Lesser God''
closed her letter with a complimentary P.S.: ``But thank you for
the nice picture.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Kennedy, the youngest son of Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy, D-Mass., underwent surgery to have a non-cancerous
tumor removed from the top of his spine and was reported in ``very
satisfactory'' condition.
   Kennedy, 20, was admitted Monday to Massachusetts General
Hospital after complaining of headaches and back pains.
   The operation Thursday was without complication and Kennedy, a
sophomore at Providence College, was expected to make a complete
recovery, said Kennedy spokesman Jeff Smith in Washington.
   Kennedy will be a Rhode Island delegate to the Democratic
National Convention in July. Like his father, he is backing Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis. He is also working on his father's re-election
campaign.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORANGEBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision to award an honorary degree
to Sen. Strom Thurmond has upset some faculty members and students
at predominantly black South Carolina State College.
   ``It's not just his old past, it's his recent past. Every single
civil rights bill since 1957 he has opposed. Right up to two weeks
ago, when he voted against the recent civil rights bill,'' said
history Professor William Hine.
   The college's board of trustees decided in February to give the
honorary doctorate of laws degree to the conservative South
Carolina Republican during graduation May 8, school President
Albert Smith said.
   Four petitions are circulating among the faculty calling for the
degree not to be awarded, Hine said, and students are talking about
boycotting graduation ceremonies.
   Thurmond will accept the award but will be out of the country on
a classified trip with the Senate Armed Services Committee, press
secretary Chris Simpson said.
</TEXT>
