<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewsmenDetained     04-23 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newsmen Detained,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Detained For Allegedly Entering Secure Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter and a photographer from a
Florida newspaper were detained for about two hours Friday after
the Coast Guard said their rented boat entered a restricted area
near a submarine shipyard.
   The reporter denied that the small boat had entered the
restricted waters, which extend 100 feet into the Thames River from
the Electric Boat Shipyard, where submarines including
nuclear-powered Tridents are built.
   The boat, rented by photographer Stanley Badz and reporter
Michael Romaner of the Jacksonville Times-Union, was stopped and
boarded after it was spotted within the restricted area, said Coast
Guard Lt. Cmdr. James Rutkovsky.
   Also aboard the 18-to-20-foot vessel was Kenneth Zelvin, a
Groton businessman who rents boats, Rutkovsky said.
   ``We didn't know what we had. We didn't know if we had
terrorists, criminals or what,'' said Rutkovsky.
   Rutkovsky said officials were concerned because the Trident
submarine Pennsylvania was being prepared for a launch Saturday.
   The three men denied being in the restricted zone, but were
taken to Coast Guard headquarters while their stories and
identities were checked, Rutkovsky said. The procedure took about
two hours, and in the end no charges were filed, he said.
   ``We weren't anywhere near 100 feet, we weren't even within 200
feet,'' Romaner said. ``You can't even get a Trident into the
camera lens from that close.''
   A Navy intelligence officer was called in and confiscated the
photographer's film. Rutkovsky said if no sensitive portions of the
shipyard were found on the film it would be returned to the
newspaper.
   The newsmen objected to the confiscation and the newspaper's
executive editor, Fred Hartmann, tried to stop the confiscation in
a telephone call to the Coast Guard, Romaner said.
</TEXT>
