<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-L'AmbianceAnniversary Bjt   04-23 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-L'Ambiance Anniversary, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Weighing Safety Changes Year After Building Collapse
Killed 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The concrete and steel rubble from L'Ambiance
Plaza has long been cleared away, but the impact of the decade's
most devastating construction accident still is being felt in
Congress.
   Lawmakers have been pushing for changes in construction-safety
laws since the partially built Bridgeport, Conn., apartment complex
collapsed one year ago today, leaving 28 workers dead.
   Proposals have ranged from tinkering with the accident reporting
requirements and stiffening criminal penalties in fatal
construction accidents to creating a separate construction agency
outside the often-criticized Occupational Safety and Health
Administration.
   ``Obviously the price is too high in all the lives lost to ever
think of it as having a silver lining,'' said Rep. Bruce A.
Morrison, D-Conn. ``But given that all of that can't be changed, I
do think it can be used ... to remind people in Congress and remind
people in OSHA'' of problems in the construction industry.
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., who was a state representative
when L'Ambiance collapsed, has devoted much of his time to the
accident since coming to Congress to replace the late Rep. Stewart
B. McKinney. But the freshman congressman is frustrated at the
slow-moving gears of Congress.
   ``Like most victims of crimes, you have the victims of
L'Ambiance who are seeing a fairly unresponsive government, or at
least a government that has responded slowly,'' Shays said in an
interview this week.
   Morrison said he is drafting legislation to increase criminal
penalties for contractors convicted in fatal construction
accidents. The current maximum penalty is six months in prison and
a $10,000 fine for willful violation of OSHA standards.
   At the request of lawmakers, OSHA is reviewing whether to change
its reporting standards. Under current regulations, only accidents
with a death or at least five injuries have to be reported.
   OSHA critics point to an accident in Stamford, Conn., shortly
before the L'Ambiance collapse that involved the same contractor
and the same type of problem that investigators say triggered the
Bridgeport accident. But the Stamford accident went unreported
because only one worker was injured.
   Morrison, who labeled the current reporting requirements
``absurd,'' believes knowledge of the Stamford accident could have
prevented L'Ambiance.
   OSHA spokesman Terry Mikelson said the reporting requirement is
still under review.
   The agency also is reviewing its regulations on the lift-slab
construction method used by L'Ambiance builders that was implicated
in the collapse.
   Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr., R-Conn., is pushing a measure that
would put the L'Ambiance fines in a special trust fund for the
victims' families. Weicker fears the heavy fines will drive the
contractors into bankruptcy, making them unable to pay damages that
could be awarded in pending civil suits.
   Some lawmakers are embracing the idea of making a separate
construction division within OSHA, while the AFL-CIO wants to
create a separate construction agency. Congressional supporters
said, however, that they do not expect action this year.
   Jim Lapping, director of safety and health for the AFL-CIO
Building and Construction Trades Department, said he does not hold
out hope for significant changes because of L'Ambiance.
   ``In '78 we had the Willow Island (cooling tower) accident (in
West Virginia) and we had 51 people killed there and nothing came
out of that,'' Lapping said.
   Such criticism of OSHA was reignited by the Bridgeport collapse,
with charges that the agency has too few inspectors and relies too
heavily on industry self-regulation.
   But OSHA officials defend their policing policies.
   ``If Congress, in its vision when it imagined what OSHA would be
like, wanted an inspector on every job site 24 hours a day, it
would have said so,'' said spokesman Mikelson. ``It made employers
accountable for safety and health, knowing full well the government
wouldn't have inspectors at every site in the country.''
   Mikelson also said OSHA has made changes in recent years,
including imposing heavier fines such as those at L'Ambiance and
severely penalizing project contractors when they fail to properly
oversee subcontractors.
   ``The bottom line is when employers show a strong commitment to
safety and health, workers sustain far fewer injures,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
