<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--TaillightLanding     04-23 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Taillight Landing,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Lands On Dark Road With Guidance From Car's Taillights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLEGAN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry ``Butch'' Miller couldn't make much
of a living as a race driver by following other cars. But he may
owe his life to the car whose taillights he followed before landing
his disabled airplane.
   Miller, 39, of Coopersville, safely landed his six-passenger
Aerostar 600 about 10 p.m. Thursday on the northbound lane of
Michigan 40 about two miles north of here.
   ``At night, it's very hard to pick out roads, if not
impossible,'' he said. ``Basically I chased the taillights. Whoever
he is he saved my life and doesn't know it.''
   The driver of the car had not been identified by late Friday,
said Deputy Susan Baker of the Allegan County Sheriff's Department.
   Miller, the defending American Speed Association stock car
racing champion, said he was en route from Huntington, Ind., to
Muskegon when the plane's right engine blew a gasket and he had to
make an emergency landing.
</TEXT>
