<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OrganizedCrime     04-23 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Organized Crime,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigator Says Mob Organized Into `Cells' Like Terrorist Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigator who almost became the first
FBI agent inducted into an organized crime family says he was
pulled out of the mob by his FBI superiors after being ordered to
kill a gangster from a rival group.
   ``The FBI felt _ and so did I _ that this was a good time for
getting out, because everybody was being killed,'' Joseph D.
Pistone told senators, explaining that he was given the hit
assignment during a mob civil war.
   Pistone also told members of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee
on Investigations there's a ``surprising similarity'' between the
structure of organized crime families and terrorist groups.
   He said ``a strict need-to-know policy is enforced,'' and fellow
mobsters often avoid telling each other their last names.
   Pistone, who spent six years working undercover with the mob,
said he was scheduled to become a ``made'' member of New York's
Bonanno family in December 1981. The FBI abruptly ended his
operation a half-year after two Bonanno factions began a civil war,
he said.
   FBI spokeswoman Kathy Bradford said that to this day, no agent
has ever become a formal ``made'' member of the mob rather than an
associate.
   Pistone testified from behind a screen because he has been
relocated and changed his appearance. But he has told his story
before, in court testimony and in a book on his six years posing as
a small-time but successful jewel thief and burglar, Donnie Brasco.
   Pistone's testimony in trials resulted in more than 200
indictments and more than 100 convictions of organized crime
members.
   Explaining the workings of mob families, Pistone said: ``There
is a surprising similarity which marks the inner-workings of the
Mafia and contemporary terrorist organizations.
   ``The families are broken down into small, separate cells,
commonly called crews.
   ``In all likelihood, a member of one crew may not even know who
are the members of another crew in his own family.''
   He said ``gambling is probably the most important source of
income'' for traditional organized crime families. Gambling
supports other mob activities, such as drug buys, payoffs, lawyer's
fees, and investments into legitimate businesses, he said.
</TEXT>
