<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugSmuggling     04-23 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Smuggling,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yost Says Coast Guard Patrol Cuts Could Be Leading To Drug Trade
Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Coast Guard says severe
cutbacks in air and sea drug patrols by the financially strapped
agency could be leading to an increase in drug trafficking along
U.S. coasts.
   ``The smugglers, when they ship, don't send us an invoice,''
said Adm. Paul A. Yost Jr. ``But we do have intelligence that
indicates the awareness by the smugglers that the Coast Guard has
cut back its patrols by ship and by air.
   ``I can only surmise that that influences their shipping
schedules'' and that there is ``some intention of taking advantage
of that,'' he said.
   The Coast Guard, faced with a $100 million budget shortfall,
earlier this year permanently shut down dozens of stations,
resulting in $40 million in savings.
   To cover the remaining $60 million, Yost ordered a 55 percent
across-the-board reduction of sea and air missions for drug
interdiction and routine search-and-rescue patrols. The cutbacks
have been in effect for about three months.
   ``Fifty-five percent of my ships are sitting alongside the dock
and planes are on the runways,'' the commandant said in interviews
this week with The Associated Press.
   ``I think that's a travesty,'' he said. ``I really think the
American people, having paid money for the ships and aircraft, and
... paying the salary of the young men and women who they've
trained to do these jobs, to have them sitting on the runway and
tied up at the dock. That ought to make the taxpayer angry.''
   Last month, President Reagan urged Congress to transfer $60
million in other Transportation Department funds, such as Amtrak,
mass transit and highway projects, to the Coast Guard to bring the
patrols back up to last year's levels. But Congress has yet to act.
   Yost said he believes he is caught in the middle of two
political realities on Capitol Hill, and that he is coming out on
the short end.
   ``What I see there is every member of Congress hates drugs and
supports and loves the Coast Guard, particularly members of our
appropriations subcommittees,'' Yost said. ``But they are forced to
choose between drug interdiction and mass transit'' projects in
their districts.
   ``I would guess very few of those members are saying, `Take my
money,''' he said.
   Yost said he sympathized with the chairmen of the transportation
funding panels, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and Rep. Bill
Lehman, D-Fla.
   ``They're both strong supporters of the Coast Guard, and yet
they have a very difficult time taking money from their grant
programs to properly fund the Coast Guard,'' he said.
   A Lehman aide said the House subcommittee may take up the Coast
Guard's funding request this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
