<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0864,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Rally In Tokyo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with closing figures, details</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices topped the 27,000-point level in an
active half-day of trading Saturday, buoyed by an overnight rally
on Wall Street, analysts said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which gained 8.96 points Friday, surged by 221.25 points to close
the half-day session at 27,058.37. It was the Nikkei's
second-highest close since April 14, when it was 27,111.35. Volume
on the first section was a moderate 470 million shares.
   ``Since there were few new incentives to affect the market
today, it's clear that investors had been waiting on the sidelines
for New York share prices to recover,'' said an analyst with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   Yoshio Shimayama, a trader with Nikko Securities, attributed the
favorable showing to the growing Japanese economy.
   ``The market is looking at the state of business in Japan, which
is very favorable. ... The major recovery in share prices in New
York overnight is also driving the market, and the overall mood of
investors here is very strong,'' Shimayama said.
   Large issues such as steels and constructions were traded
actively, along with electricals such as Sony and Toshiba.
   Buy orders for Toshiba Corp., targeted for penalty sanctions in
an omnibus trade bill approved by the U.S. House of Representatives
Thursday, totaled more than 6.1 million shares, compared with
730,000 sell orders.
   ``It indicates the (positive) mood of market investors,'' the
Nomura analyst said.
   The Tokyo foreign exchange is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
