<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GlobalClassroom Bjt   04-23 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Global Classroom, Bjt,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students In Four Countries Play Diplomat Via Computer Links</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College students in 10 states and three
countries are linking up by computer to simulate global bargaining
for peace. But they're finding make-believe hostilities are often
as touchy as in real life.
   In the first few days of the exercise this semester, Iran
rejected Iraq's offer to end their war as ``treachery'' and the
Soviet Union dispatched a flurry of communiques calling the United
States ``offensive.''
   The 700 students are playing diplomat as part of the
International Communication and Negotiation Simulations program,
based at the University of Maryland.
   ``We're not doing an adequate job in American education of
teaching how to live and function in an interdependent world,''
said Jonathan Wilkenfeld, a government and politics professor at
the college who co-directs the program. ``It's only been in recent
years that we have discovered a need to become more of a part of
issues that other countries find important.''
   One scenario envisioned by the students, who work six months in
the future, proved all too real.
   ``We assassinated (Egyptian President Anwar) Sadat about three
months before it really happened,'' said Wilkenfeld, who encourages
students to seek solutions through peaceful negotiation. ``We felt
badly about that.''
   ICONS began in 1981 with a grant from the U.S. Education
Department. In its early days, the program involved three or four
universities. This semester, 15 universities are participating
through computer links from the University of Maryland to
Tennessee, New Jersey, North Carolina, California, Pennsylvania,
Utah, Vermont, Wyoming and Wisconsin.
   The computer also links American students to others in France,
Argentina and Japan. Messages during the five-week simulation often
are sent in foreign languages and must be translated with care so
sensitive correspondence is not misunderstood. With students living
in various time zones, setting up computer conferences often
becomes a logistical nightmare.
   The simulations are based on a scenario of world events written
before the game begins each semester. The scenario takes what's
happening in the world and projects it six to eight months ahead,
Bass said. That way, students are not tempted to read newspapers
and magazines looking for negotiating tips and strategies, she said.
   In the first few days of this semester's simulation, the
Soviets, played by students at Brigham Young University in Provo,
Utah, sent out more than 100 messages, said Doreen Bass, simulation
director and a member of the University of Maryland's research
faculty.
   ``A lot of it was cold war rhetoric and the United States
(students at Maryland) sent a response saying it was not pleased
with what it called propaganda,'' Bass said.
   Two days later, the ``Soviets'' rebutted:
   ``The Soviet leadership and people were deeply wounded and
pained by the offensive and insensitive communique received from
the United States this week,'' the Brigham Young team wrote. ``We
are all concerned and troubled to find that the cold war still
rages in the hearts of American leaders.''
   Meanwhile, the Iranian team, played by a different group of
Maryland students, was busy composing a reply to the Iraqi team's
offer to terminate its involvement in the Iran-Iraq war.
   ``Iraq sent out a message saying they were unilaterally
withdrawing from the war, returning all Iranian POWs, returning all
borders to original pre-war positions,'' said Adam Pinchuck, a
member of the Iranian team. ``We flatly rejected it and said it was
`filled with duplicity and treachery and horrific lies.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
