<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TurnpikeExplosives     04-23 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turnpike Explosives,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Files 12-Count Indictment Against Man Arrested on
Turnpike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese man linked by authorities to the
terrorist Red Army has been indicted for carrying pipe bombs on the
New Jersey Turnpike, officials said.
   Yu Kikumura, 35, was charged with three counts of interstate
transport of explosive devices, three counts of possessing
unregistered explosive devices and three counts of possession of
explosives by an illegal alien, U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr.
said Friday.
   Kikumura, identified by the Japanese Foreign Ministry as a
suspected member of the terrorist Red Army group, also was charged
with one count each of having an illegal passport, a fraudulent
visa and the passport of another person, Alito said.
   The charges together carry a prison term of up to 90 years.
   Police in Milan, Italy, said Thursday that Kikumura spent a few
days in a city hotel in February prior to an April 14 car bombing
allegedly staged by the Red Army. The blast killed an American
servicewoman and four Italians outside a USO club in Naples.
   FBI experts haved traveled to Italy to try to determine whether
Kikumura was linked to those involved in the bombing.
   He was arrested April 12 at a service area on the turnpike in
Ridgefield after a state trooper found the sophisticated homemade
bombs and falsified papers, authorities said.
   Officials said Kikumura used a passport stolen from a Japanese
hospital worker to obtain a U.S. entry visa from the U.S. Embassy
in Paris on Feb. 29. He entered the country on March 8, authorities
said.
   Ronald Kuby, who along with noted radical defense attorney
William Kunstler is defending Kikumura, said he found the number of
charges incredible.
   ``You've taken a straightforward single offense, multiplied it,
pyramided it until you face a century in jail,'' Kuby said,
comparing it to a person arrested for distributing drugs and facing
a separate count for each unit of the drug sold.
   ``He is being indicted for what the government thinks he is
rather than what he has done,'' Kuby said.
   Kikumura is being held without bail in the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in New York without bail.
   Alito said he is to be arraigned next Friday in Newark before
U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner Jr.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880423-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     04-23 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Campaign Entering New Phase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said following his first
one-on-one debate with Michael Dukakis the presidential campaign
has begun ``a new phase'' in which differences between the two
Democrats will be more clearly spelled out.
   Pressed by reporters about differences between the two remaining
Democratic contenders, Jackson said Friday nigt Dukakis has not
been forthcoming in detailing how he would translate his
``Massachusetts miracle'' into solutions to aid the nation's
economy.
   As Massachusetts governor, Dukakis takes much of the credit for
his state's 2.9 percent unemployment rate, its plant-closings
notice law and America's first universal health-insurance law.
   But Jackson, speaking at the University of Pennsylvania four
days before the state's primary, said Dukakis ``so far has made out
no budget.''
   ``There must be some budget in order to establish priorities, in
order to establish the plan,'' Jackson said.
   ``You simply cannot afford a decent job for everybody at good
wages, and you cannot afford houses for everybody in this country
unless you are going to make some judgments about shifting
priorities,'' Jackson said. ``I'm willing to debate ways to pay for
the dream.''
   Jackson said he has called for a plan to freeze the military
budget over the next five years, and that ``I have put forth a
comprehensive plan to fight the war on drugs. The governor has
not.''
   Still, Jackson said he was wary of ``fracturing'' the party, and
said he hoped there could be ``distinction without division.''
   Jackson spoke to reporters after a good-natured, hour-long
debate with Dukakis, their first such confrontation since Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. dropped out of the race after the New York
primary on Tuesday.
   Another debate was planned for tonight in Pittsburgh, where
Jackson's support is shakier than in Philadelphia. In Philadelphia,
Jackson has the support of the mayor and numerous other local
elected officials.
   Later Friday night, Jackson told a rocking congregation at the
Calvin Presbyterian Church in west Philadelphia that the debate
``begins a new phase of the campaign'' in which a less crowded
field will enable voters to become more familiar with individual
candidates.
   He was flanked at the podium by his mother, Helen; Mayor W.
Wilson Goode; Councilman Lucien Blackwell; State Rep. David
Richardson of Philadelphia; and actress Margot Kidder, a supporter
who has joined Jackson previously on the campaign trail.
   Earlier, Jackson addressed students at nearby West Chester State
University, and announced a plan and a budget for a national
child-care program with a $5.3 billion price tag.
   The plan calls for an increase in child-care assistance for
families with low and moderate incomes and a strategy to use public
schools for befo re-school and after-school programs.
</TEXT>
