<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Ramsey     04-23 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Ramsey,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Archbishop Of Canterbury Lord Ramsey Dies At 83</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Archbishop of Canterbury Lord Ramsey, a
kindly, craggy Christian and brilliant debater who traveled the
world in his passion to unite its divided churches, died early
today, the Church of England said. He was 83.
   Ramsey was president of the World Council of Churches from 1961
to 1968.
   The church press office said in a statement that he died at St.
John's Home, a residence for elderly people in Oxford, after being
ill for several weeks with bronchial pneumonia.
   His wife, Lady Ramsey, was at his side when he died peacefully
at about 2 a.m. (9 p.m. EDT Friday).
   As Archbishop of Canterbury from 1961 to 1974, he was spiritual
head of the Church of England and leader of the world's 70 million
Anglicans, including the 3 million U.S. Episcopalians.
   Ramsey took a liberal stand on a wide variety of political and
social issues of his day.
   He condemned the U.S. bombing of North Vietnam during the
Vietnam War, called for Britain to discard its nuclear weapons
unilaterally and campaigned for relaxation of the laws restricting
homosexuality, divorce and abortion.
   Ramsey demanded the abolition of the death penalty, was an
outspoken opponent of South Africa's apartheid policy of racial
separation and opposed restrictions on the admission of Asian
immigrants into Britain.
   At his enthronement as Archbishop of Canterbury, Ramsey
described his objectives as ``the unity of Christians.''
   The Church of England was at the time in process of a long
decline, with dwindling church attendance and a diminishing role in
the everyday lives of ordinary Britons.
   But Ramsey pushed the Church toward Christian reunion, which he
predicted might come about before the end of this century, and made
it aware of the world beyond England.
   His passion to reunite the Christian churches _ the
Nonconformist, the Anglican, the Eastern Orthodox, and the Roman
Catholic, divided over the centuries _ took him to more countries
than any other Archbishop of Canterbury before him.
   Ramsey was bitterly disappointed when the General Synod of the
Church of England in 1972 rejected union with the Methodists.
   His air of craggy Christian kindness, as one newspaper described
it, inspired trust and confidence among those who met him.
   Michael Ramsey was born on Nov. 14, 1904, the son of a lecturer
in mathematics at Cambridge University. His paternal grandfather
was a Congregationalist minister and his maternal grandfather was
an Anglican clergyman.
   He was educated at Cambridge, ordained in 1928, and became
Bishop of Durham in 1952 and Archbishop of York in 1956.
   Ramsey was made a life peer on his retirement as archbishop in
1974 and took the title of Lord Ramsey of Canterbury.
   He was succeeded by Donald Coggan, who retired from the post in
1980. The current Archbishop of Canterbury is Robert Runcie.
   A funeral service for Ramsey will be held in historic Canterbury
Cathedral in southeast England and a memorial service is also
planned at London's Westminster Abbey, the statement said. No dates
have yet been set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
