<HEAD>Justice Department Seeks Extension For Overseas Voters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department has filed
suit for an extension of the time people living outside the country
have to get their absentee ballots in for next Tuesday's
Pennsylvania primary.
   The department said Friday that many absentee ballots were not
mailed by the state to Americans living abroad in time for the
ballots to be counted by the current deadline of 5 p.m. on the
Friday before the election.
   This is the first time the department has filed such a lawsuit
under the Uniformed and Overseas Citizens Absentee Voting Act of
1986, said William Bradford Reynolds, head of the department's
civil rights division.
   The lawsuit was filed in U.S. District Court in Harrisburg.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania GOP Posts Slight Registration Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania Republicans are gaining
ground on the Democratic registration majority, state figures show.
   Statistics released Friday showed Democrats lost 12,723 voters
since last November's election. During the same period, the GOP
picked up 17,239 voters.
   Despite the slight gains by the Republicans, Democrats still
held a significant majority statewide. Overall, there were 2.85
million Democrats compared with 2.28 Republican voters, according
to the figures.
