<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0606EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RacismConference     04-23 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Racism Conference,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Administrators, Faculty Discuss Campus Racism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasing racial tensions on campus
in recent years can be partly blamed on the ``self-centered''
ethics of students in the 1980s, educators and students were told
at a conference.
   Not only have colleges failed to teach students about ethics,
but the Reagan administration has undermined gains in civil rights,
contributing to a rise in racism, sexism and homophobia on
campuses, some educators said.
   ``There's been a reversal in students from the 1960s,'' said
Kenneth B. Clark, a psychologist and professor emeritus at the City
University of New York, who has researched the effects of
segregation on children. ``They are more self-centered and less
socially conscious.''
   The conference at Rutgers University was attended Friday by more
than 250 teachers, administrators and students from about 30 New
Jersey colleges. Sponsored by the state Department of Higher
Education and the National Conference of Christians and Jews, its
intent was to alert college leaders to the problems of intolerance
and suggest possible solutions.
   But the educators said recent student protests over minority
concerns at a number of colleges nationwide were encouraging.
   ``In part it's a good thing in the sense that it reflects a
determination by minority kids not to take this treatment,'' said
Meyer Weinberg, professor of Education at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, where students occupied an administration
building in February to protest campus racism.
   Those who attended the conference were treated to their own bit
of protest when a group of student demonstrators took the stage
even though the state's Chancellor of Higher Education, T. Edward
Hollander, refused them permission to speak.
   Hollander said later he was ``delighted'' to see them insist on
speaking out.
   ``I've waited 10 years for students to show that kind of
interest,'' he said.
   Hollander said organizers asked colleges to send students and
officials to the conference ``who hold the power'' to make campuses
aware of the state's effort to curb intolerance.
   The protesters spoke up after the keynote speech by Mayor Henry
Cisneros of San Antonio. They criticized the pace of reform and
said conference organizers failed to invite student and community
activists.
   ``We feel this is just a PR event to appease the community and
falsely give the sense that the colleges are resolving racist
relationships,'' said Salaam Ismail, coordinator of the Union of
African Organizations of Students, which represents colleges
statewide.
   The protesters had kind words for Cisneros, mayor since 1981,
who urged administrators to preach against intolerance and ensure
that graduates are able to contribute to a diverse society.
   He said changing demographics, rising immigration from Central
America, competition from Asian countries and a stagnant economy
require that Americans work together in a spirit of cooperation.
   Cisneros said students should gain an ``education in reality''
by volunteering for community service and that universities should
strive to develop minority leaders.
   Earlier Friday, in Williamstown, Mass., about 30 minority
students took over a dean's office at Williams College.
   A spokesman for the protesters said that black, Hispanic, Asian
and Polynesian students occupied Jenness House to protest what they
say is the administration's unwillingness to address minority
concerns at the prestigious liberal arts college.
   Also Friday, a group of minority students and University of
Vermont officials reached agreement to end the students' four-day
occupation of the college president's office. The agreement calls
for the university to increase the number of minority faculty
members and students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880423-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KidsStabbed     04-23 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kids Stabbed,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Stabbed As Parents Take Part In Child Abuse Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old boy was stabbed to death and
two other boys were wounded as they waited in a van outside a
Christian TV station where their parents were participating in a
child abuse program, police said.
   Authorities had no suspects in what may have been a robbery
attempt Friday night, said Monroe police Lt. James Weems.
   Stephen K. Parker was killed in the attack. His brother, Chad M.
Parker, 11, was reported in stable condition early today at St.
Francis Medical Center. Benjamin J. Hobson, 11, was in intensive
care unit at St. Francis, reported in critical condition.
   The Parker boys were the sons of the Rev. Mike Parker of
Sterlington Assembly of God Church and his wife.
   The Parkers and Tommy Hobson, owner of the van and Benjamin's
father, were in the studio of KMCT-TV doing a gospel show's live
broadcast at the time, said Randy Self, the Parker boys' uncle.
   Self said Chad Parker heard someone knocking on the van door,
and, thinking it was his mother, opened the door and was stabbed in
the eye.
   He said Chad told him a second man also got into the van and
started stabbing the two other boys.
   Chad said one of the men asked how much money the boys had and
then said, ``I want it,'' Self said.
   Bill Snearly, former production manager for KMCT who lives in
the studio complex, said just before the stabbing he saw two males
walking toward the van in the parking lot.
   He quoted Chad as saying, ```When we opened the door, they
started stabbing us with butcher knives and hitting us with the
handles.''
   Snearly said Chad was covered with blood when he crawled into
the studio where his father was taking part in the broadcast about
child abuse.
   A Monroe policeman who had been called to the studio to unlock a
car arrived just after the stabbings, Snearly said.
   ``The officer actually caught the kid that died just as he was
stumbling out of the van,'' Snearly said.
   At the time of the stabbing, about 40 people were in the
television studio, which Snearly said was ``maybe 30 steps'' from
the van.
   Snearly said he was bewildered by the incident.
   ``They stole the boys' money,'' he said. ``Now, how much money
could they get off three kids that age.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
