<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka     04-23 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 12 Die In Rebel Raid On Air Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese rebels attacked the
country's main air force base and battled troops for four hours
before fleeing with stolen weapons. Officials said at least seven
rebels and five servicemen were killed.
   Also Friday, guerrillas from the same group raided a radio
station and stole communications equipment, authorities said.
   The military said the People's Liberation Front rebels ignited
bombs ``as diversionary measures'' and stabbed two guards Friday
night to enter Katunayake air base, 16 miles north of Colombo.
   The officials, who under briefing rules spoke on condition of
anonymity, said five rebels, 24 servicemen and four policemen were
injured in the air base battle, during which flights were halted at
the adjacent Colombo international airport.
   At least three rebels were captured, but their comrades managed
to escape with at least 30 Chinese made T-56 rifles and a machine
gun, the officials said.
   It was the rebel group's second attack on the air base. On June
8, a similar attack was repulsed.
   The rebels also attacked a radio station of the government-owned
Posts and Telecommunication Department, said Telecommunication
officer J.M. Peries. Peries said two employees were stabbed and
were in critical condition today.
   He said the rebels stole radio equipment, but some of it was
later recovered.
   The People's Liberation Front began as a radical Marxist group,
but now champions rights of the island's majority Sinhalese. It was
outlawed after a failed 1971 attempt to overthrow the government,
and regrouped in 1986.
   The front has opposed the July 29 peace accord between India and
Sri Lanka, which was aimed at ending the four-year separatist
rebellion by the minority Tamils. The front contends the accord
makes too many concessions to the Tamils and has vowed to kill
anyone who supports it.
   The Tamils, who are mainly Hindu, compose about 18 percent of
Sri Lanka's 16 million people. They claim they are discriminated
against by the Buddhist Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the
population and control the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
