<DOCNO> AP880423-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0614EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Minister-Suit     04-23 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minister-Suit,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Minister Liable For Attack On His Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state district judge has ruled that Walker
Railey, a former prominent Methodist minister, ``maliciously and
brutally tried to strangle his wife'' in an attack that left her in
a coma.
   Judge John Whittington issued the judgment Friday in a civil
lawsuit filed by Peggy Railey's mother, Billie Jo Nicolai.
Whittington, quoting from the lawsuit, also ruled Railey
established a ``false alibi'' to cover his actions.
   The default judgment was announced a year and a day after Mrs.
Railey, 39, was found lying unconscious on her garage floor. She
has been comatose since the attack.
   Although he was served twice with the suit, Railey, 40, never
responded in court to the allegation that he attacked his wife,
though he has denied it out of court.
   ``If you bring allegations against the defendant and you give
the defendant notice of the allegations and an opportunity to come
in and respond to those allegations, and he refuses to do that, the
court can hold the defendant liable and hold those allegations as
true,'' said Bill Arnold, Mrs. Nicolai's attorney.
   Arnold said a jury trial should determine this summer the
damages Railey will be ordered to pay. Arnold said he will seek
actual damages for Mrs. Railey's past and future medical bills and
punitive damages for the pain and suffering of Mrs. Railey and her
family.
   Railey, the former senior minister at Dallas' First United
Methodist Church, has said he was doing research on the Southern
Methodist University campus the night his wife was attacked.
   After a suicide attempt following the attack, Railey refused to
talk with police and refused to answer questions before a grand
jury investigating the attack.
   Railey surrendered his ministerial credentials and moved to San
Francisco, where he rented an apartment with Lucy Papillon, a
psychologist who told a grand jury she had been seeing Railey
before the attack and that they had discussed marriage.
   The Raileys' two children are living with family friends in
Dallas.
   In his ``findings of fact,'' Whittington wrote ``that on or
about April 21, 1987, the defendant Walker L. Railey intentionally,
knowingly, maliciously and brutally attempted to strangle his wife
Peggy Railey to death.
   ``The Court further finds the defendant then left Mrs. Railey
for dead, left his two young children _ Ryan, age 5, and Megan, age
2 _ alone in the house without supervision, and drove to the
Fondren Library at Southern Methodist University in an attempt to
conceal his actions and to establish a false alibi for his
wherabouts at the time of the assault,'' the judge wrote.
   ``My clients are very pleased,'' said Arnold, who plans to
subpoena Railey for the trial and seek a warrant for his arrest.
   Railey's attorney, Doug Mulder, was not in his office or at home
when phoned for comment and did return messages.
   The civil judgment has no bearing on a criminal investigation
that officials say is stalled because of insufficient evidence.
Railey has not been charged with any crime, but his attorney
identified him as the chief suspect in the case.
   Investigators say they believe Railey is now in the Los Angeles
area.
</TEXT>
