<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DetainedNewsmen     04-23 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detained Newsmen,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newsmen Detained After They Allegedly Enter Secure Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter and photographer for a Florida
newspaper were detained after they allegedly entered a 100-foot
restricted area around a submarine shipyard where a Trident sub was
scheduled to be launched today.
   Michael Romaner, photographer Stanley Badz and the skipper of
their boat, Kenneth Zelvin, were detained for more than two hours
Friday. The Coast Guard accused Zelvin's vessel of entering the
restricted area around Electric Boat Shipyard.
   The newsmen had chartered Zelvin's boat to take pictures of
submarines at the yard for The Florida Times-Union of Jacksonville.
   Witnesses from the Coast Guard and Electric Boat reported the
boat entered restricted waters, which extend 100 feet into the
Thames River from the shipyard, Lt. Cmdr. James Rutkovsky said.
   ``We didn't know what we had. We didn't know if we had
terrorists, criminals or what,'' he said.
   Rutkovsky said officials were concerned because the Trident
submarine Pennsylvania was being prepared for launch today. Other
submarines in various stages of construction also are at the
shipyard.
   ``We weren't anywhere near 100 feet, we weren't even within 200
feet,'' Romaner said.
   A Navy intelligence officer confiscated the photographer's film.
Rutkovsky said if no sensitive portions of the shipyard are found
on the film it will be returned to the newspaper.
   The newspaper's executive editor, Fred Hartmann, tried to stop
the confiscation in a telephone call to the Coast Guard, Romaner
said.
   The Pennsylvania is the 10th ship in the Navy's Trident force.
It will carry a crew of 154 and be armed with 24 Trident II
missiles.
   The nuclear-powered Tridents, or Ohio Class submarines, are the
largest and most powerful in the Navy fleet. Electric Boat, a
division of defense giant General Dynamics Corp., is their sole
builder.
</TEXT>
