<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--NeedleTheft     04-23 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Needle Theft,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man With Hypodermic Charged with Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been charged with robbery after he
allegedly held a hypodermic needle next to a woman's neck and
threatened to give her AIDS if she did not hand over her jewelry.
   Richard Colon, 23, of the Bronx told police after his arrest
Friday that he did not have acquired immune deficiency syndrome but
that he was an intravenous drug user, said Sgt. Maurice Howard, a
department spokesman.
   Several needles were found in his possession before he was
charged, the spokesman said.
   The victim, Arelys Gonzales, a 21-year-old Bronx woman, told
police that Colon came up behind her on Monday night, held the
needle to her neck, said he had AIDS and would give it to her
unless she gave him her ring, earrings and watch, Howard said.
   She gave him the jewelry, valued at $500, he said.
   Gonzales recognized the man near there on Friday night and
called police, Howard said. The jewelry was not recovered.
</TEXT>
