<DOCNO> AP880423-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0638EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     04-23 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Leave Without Hostages, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered Swiss executive jet carrying
negotiators seeking the release of three French hostages took off
from Beirut airport today without any of the missing men, airport
officials said.
   The plane's arrival in Beirut from Larnaca, Cyprus, two hours
earlier fueled speculation it had come for the Frenchmen and their
release was imminent. The three have been held by Shiite Moslem
extremists since 1985.
   The airport officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
they did not know the destination of the 12-seat Falcon 50 jet. But
radio monitors in Cyprus heard the pilot tell Larnaca tower he was
heading for Paris.
   A senior Beirut airport official said there were four French
negotiatiors aboard the Falcon 50 when it left Beirut today. He
said the four flew into Beirut Friday on the same jet, which spent
Friday night in Larnaca.
   ``None of the hostages was with them'' when they left Beirut,
the official said.
   The plane left Beirut today after radio reports said
negotiations to free the hostages had hit a snag, apparently after
the kidnappers made last-minute demands.
   Asked whether the latest effort to release the Frenchmen had
collapsed, the airport official said: ``I don't know. I can't
tell.''
   A source close to the command of a 7,500-man Syrian army force
in charge of security in Moslem west Beirut had said Friday night
that the French hostages would be released in ``a matter of
hours.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The three Frenchmen are diplomats Marcel Fontaine and Marcel
Carton and journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann. Fontaine and Carton were
kidnapped separately March 22, 1985, Kauffmann two months later.
   A fourth Frenchman, researcher Michel Seurat, was kidnapped May
22, 1985. The extremist group Islamic Jihad, or Holy War, claimed
10 months later that it had killed him.
   Although no body has been found, Seurat's wife, Marie, said in a
book she published last month that French officials have told her
he died in captivity.
   Two other French hostages, photo-journalist Roger Auque and
television lighting engineer Jean-Louis Normandin, were released
Nov. 27 by Shiite kidnappers Nov. 27.
   The French government of Prime Minister Jacques Chirac has been
trying to free the three men before the first round of the French
presidential elections Sunday.
   In addition to the French captives, 18 other foreigners are
missing in Beirut. They are nine Americans, three Britons, a West
German, an Italian, an Irishman, an Indian and two unidentified
foreign men.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, Associated Press chief
Middle East corrpespondet, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
