<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Bring Rain, Hail And Snow To Much Of The
Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wintry storm system spawned thunderstorms that swept across
much of the nation today, dumping rain, snow and hail along the way.
   The storm system tracked into central Illinois late Friday,
setting off thunderstorms early this morning from Illinois through
northern Indiana, into southern Michigan and northwest Ohio. The
storms were moving into western parts of Indiana and brought hail,
gusty winds and brief heavy rain.
   Illinois received the brunt of the storm activity Friday night.
A tornado touched down near Butler, destroying a barn. Hail the
size of golf balls pelted parts of northwestern Illinois, while in
Burbank, the ground was whitened by a deluge of hail.
   Severe thunderstorms also were reported across southern, lower
Michigan and northwest Ohio.
   Snow was scattered over southern Minnesota, southeastern South
Dakota and northern Nebraska. Meanwhile, highways over southwest
Minnesota were covered with slush Friday night, creating hazardous
driving conditions.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
lower Great Lakes through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys; possible
severe thunderstorms over parts of southern Indiana, central and
southern Ohio, southwest Pennsylvania, northern and western West
Virginia, Kentucky, Tenneessee, northwestern Alabama and northern
Mississippi; snow scattered from the upper Mississippi Valley into
Michigan; snow likely from eastern Minnesota through northern
Wisconsin and over the mountains of northern Arizona; showers
scattered over the northern and middle Mississippi Valley and
across the Southeast into the mid-Atlantic region; showers from the
Pacific Northwest into the central mountain region; and numerous
showers across central California.
   Highs will be in the 50s or 60s across much of the nation; in
the 30s from northern Minnesota into upper Michigan; in the 40s
from central Wyoming through Nebraska into the upper Great Lakes;
in the 70s across the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys into North
Carolina; in the 80s from western and central Texas through the
lower Mississippi Valley and southeastern states into Florida; and
in the low 90s across southern Texas and interior Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 19
degrees at Custer, S.D., to 83 at Laredo, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 67 cloudy; Boston 41 fair; Buffalo 35 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 65 cloudy; Cincinnati 55 fair; Cleveland 49
cloudy; Detroit 45 cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York 47 fair;
Philadelphia 43 fair; Pittsburgh 49 cloudy; Portland, Maine 38
fair; Washington 50 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 23 fair; Chicago 44 showers; Dallas-Fort
Worth 66 fair; Denver 29 freezing drizzle; Des Moines 43 drizzle;
Indianapolis 55 cloudy; Kansas City 42 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul
35 snow; Nashville 70 cloudy; New Orleans 75 foggy; St. Louis 63
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 44 fair; Anchorage 37 cloudy; Las Vegas 55
fair; Los Angeles 57 partly cloudy; Phoenix 60 fair; Salt Lake City
45 partly cloudy; San Diego 59 cloudy; San Francisco 49 rain;
Seattle 47 foggy.
   _Canada: Montreal 36 fair; Toronto 34 cloudy.
</TEXT>
