<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Jagger     04-23 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Jagger,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rocker Takes Stand in Copyright Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mick Jagger half-sang, half-spoke some
of the Rolling Stones' greatest hits from the witness stand as he
tried to prove he didn't steal a song from a reggae musician.
   Jagger swayed to the beat and came close to singing Friday as he
recited for a judge, jury and fans who packed the courtroom,
``Jumpin' Jack Flash, it's a gas, gas, gas.''
   Jagger was trying to show how he uses repetition in his lyrics,
as part of his defense against a charge by Patrick Alley, who is
suing for copyright infringement, claiming Jagger's 1985 solo hit
``Just Another Night'' was copied from his 1979 song of the same
name.
   The choruses in both songs use the phrase ``Just another night''
repeatedly.
   Jagger has denied he stole the song, which he said he didn't
hear until the suit was filed in 1986.
   He has testified for two days, playing tapes of the song as it
was written and arranged in 1983 and 1984 to try to show the
independent development of the piece.
   In Friday's session, he quoted lyrics from ``Brown Sugar,''
``Miss You,'' and ``Let's Spend the Night Together.''
   Jagger testified that repetition is common in popular music.
   Tapes were played of at least six different versions of the
tune, recorded in various places with various people in 1984. The
version that was released was recorded in May 1984 in Nassau, the
Bahamas, with a drummer named Sly Dunbar.
   Alley claims Dunbar played for his recording in 1979. Dunbar has
testified that he didn't remember whether he played for Alley or
not.
   Jagger testified that the title and lyrics to the song went
through a metamorphosis, starting with ``Another Night,'' and
``just another something else'' while he was ``messing around'' to
develop the music.
   He couldn't remember when he finished the lyrics or title.
   Jagger admitting playing reggae music with the late reggae
musician Peter Tosh, but said he didn't tend to listen to radio
stations that played that kind of music.
   He said he acknowledged works of other artists and paid them
royalties.
   Alley's lawyers have said Jagger's version netted as much as $6
million.
   The chorus of Alley's song goes, ``Can I spend another, just
another night, just another night, just another night with you.''
   Jagger's lines are, ``Give me just another night, just another
night with you. Give me just another kiss, just before the dawn
breaks through.''
   After his testimony, expected to continue Monday, Jagger signed
autographs and told reporters he thought the case was going well.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880423-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua     04-23 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Accuses Washington Of Sending Arms In Violation Of Peace
Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega accused the
United States of concealing arms in shipments of non-lethal aid to
rebels and said the White House is encouraging the military
hardliners in the Contra leadership.
   At a news conference Friday, Ortega also urged the United States
to resume negotiations on ``national security'' matters of mutual
concern, suggesting the first meeting be held May 15 in Mexico.
   The Nicaraguan leader said he was taking up President Reagan on
a promise of talks Reagan made in November when he told the
Organization of American States that Secretary of State George P.
Shultz was prepared to meet with Nicaraguan officials ``once
serious negotiations'' on a Nicaraguan cease-fire were under way.
   ``We have met with the Contras, there is a cease-fire, there is
an agreement and the time has come for the U.S. government to show
consistency by meeting with Nicaragua to discuss matters of
national security,'' Ortega said.
   He suggested the meetings begin May 15 at the Mexican west coast
resort of Manzanillo, where the two nations held talks that ended
unsucessfully in January 1985.
   Ortega said the leftist Sandinista government's ambassador to
Washington, Carlos Tunnerman, would deliver a formal proposal in a
few days.
   Ortega accused the United States of encouraging military
hardliners in the Contra leadership by deciding to give the rebels
non-lethal aid in violation of the preliminary peace accord his
government signed with the Contras March 23.
   He also claimed the United States was concealing weapons and
ammunition in shipments of humanitarian aid to rebels in Honduran
camps.
   The preliminary accord allows humanitarian aid to be distributed
through neutral international organizations, but only after the
rebels have settled in seven cease-fire zones inside Nicaragua
during the first half of May.
   Ortega said that non-lethal aid, most of it food, was already
being flown from Toncontin Airport in Tegucigalpa, the Honduran
capital, to camps controlled by Contra commanders who oppose the
cease-fire.
   An official of the U.S. Agency for International Development,
which is handling the shipments, said Thursday that the first
truckloads of food arrived at rebel camps inside Honduras this week.
   He said they were sent from Tegucigalpa after being inspected by
independent observers to make sure they did not contain arms.
   The March 23 preliminary peace accord signed in the southern
border town of Sapoa established a 60-day cease-fire than began
April 1 and during which both sides are charged with seeking to
negotiate a lasting peace in the 6{-year-old conflict that has cost
more than 26,000 lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
