<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF-BuildingGlare     04-23 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Building Glare,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronomers Complain About Lights From New Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amateur astronomers say bright lights atop a
new high-rise office building are preventing them from seeing stars
and planets.
   Members of the Amateur Astronomy Association of Pittsburgh say
the light shooting upward from the 31-story Fifth Avenue Place
amounts to ``light pollution.''
   Astronomers also claim the lights cause a haze that interferes
with their gazing miles from downtown.
   ``It's a nuisance,'' said Tom Reiland, president of the
250-member group. ``If you are an amateur who is hunting for comets
... a light like that could reduce your possibilities of being able
to discover (them).''
   Andy Gildersleeve, project manager of the building, said workers
were experimenting with the lighting. He said the lights' intensity
likely would diminish after experimentation.
   But he said it was likely the building would remain the
brightest in the city.
</TEXT>
