<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     04-23 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General Opens Formal Investigation Of Mecham Remarks On
Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona's attorney general has launched a
formal investigation into whether former Gov. Evan Mecham broke the
law when he urged supporters to ``have a lapse of memory'' about
their support for him if they become potential jurors at his
criminal trial.
   Attorney General Bob Corbin said Friday he decided to launch the
probe after first looking into whether Mecham's statements,
``assuming they are true,'' could be a violation of criminal
statutes.
   Mecham acknowledged Thursday he made the remark Monday during an
invitation-only Republican meeting, but said he was only joking.
   Told Friday that Corbin had decided on a formal investigation,
Mecham said ``I have no objection to his investigating anything he
wants'' and declined further comment.
   Corbin said the investigation will be to determine whether
Mecham violated one of several laws, including the solicitation
law, which prohibits asking somebody to commit or help commit a
crime.
   Corbin said he did not think the investigation would result in a
delay of Mecham's May 19 trial on six felony charges of fraud,
perjury and filing false documents for failing to report a $350,000
loan to his 1986 campaign. Mecham's brother and 1986 campaign
treasurer, Willard Mecham, faces three similar counts.
   On Thursday, Mecham told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview, ``Somebody asked if we could get a fair trial. I said
(no) unless we could get some people who were friendly that might
have a lapse of memory'' when they were questioned about whether
they could be impartial.
   ``I said it tongue-in-cheek. In fact, everybody laughed about
it,'' Mecham said. ``I'm not going to quit talking ... just because
we've got a bunch of people without a sense of humor.''
   Mecham was removed from office April 4 upon his conviction by
the Arizona Senate on impeachment charges that he attempted to
thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat and that he
misused a protocol fund by loaning $80,000 from it to his car
dealership.
</TEXT>
