<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     04-23 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Claim Capture Of Strategic Soviet-Afghan Garrison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas claimed today that
they captured a strategic Soviet-Afghan garrison after a four-month
siege.
   The Peshawar headquarters of the seven-party Mujahedeen alliance
said Barikot, in Afghanistan's northeast Kunar province, fell
Friday. The alliance said the capture will boost their supply flow
over the Pakistan-Afghanistan border.
   Spokesmen said the base and village were heavily fortified and
served as the headquarters of Communist Afghanistan's 55th army
brigade.
   The rebels, led by Commander Rahmatullah of the Hezb-i-Islami
Khalis faction reported that helicopters airlifted five infantry
and commando battalions before the insurgents overran the compound
around 1 p.m.
   Soviet and Afghan aircraft indiscriminately bombed and shelled
the Barikot area during the first stage of the attack, destroying
dozens of houses, guerrillas said.
   The rebels said 17 of their fighters died and 16 were wounded
but they had no casualty figures for Soviet-Afghan troops.
   Barikot lies just inside the Afghan border with northern
Pakistan.
   There was no immediate confirmation of the report but if
accurate, it would be a major victory for the anti-communist
guerrillas and would open a new direct supply route from Pakistan
of U.S., Saudi and Chinese weapons.
   Pakistan is a staging area for the Afghan resistance although
Islamabad has pledged in an April 14 Soviet troop withdrawal accord
to stop serving as an arms conduit when the agreement goes into
effect on May 15.
   Under the agreement, the Soviets agreed to withdraw its
estimated 115,000 troops over a nine-month period, beginning May
15. The Soviets intervened in December 1979.
</TEXT>
