<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Tanker,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>28 Crew Members Still Missing as Greek Tanker Burns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities scaled down an air
and sea search today as hope dwindled for finding any survivors
among the 29 people who were aboard a Greek tanker that broke up in
a fire.
   Seven merchant ships helping to scour the area about 370 miles
southeast of Cape Race, Newfoundland, were told today they could
abandon the search, said Petty Officer Brad Terrill of the U.S.
Coast Guard in New York.
   Early today, the stern of the 18,000-ton tanker was still
ablaze. The bow sank Friday in rain squalls and winds exceeding 55
mph that whipped up 5-foot swells.
   On Friday night, searchers recovered the badly burned body of a
crewman, Andrej Szukalski, 41, of Poland. The other 28 people
aboard _ 23 Polish sailors and five of their wives _ remained
missing.
   The 500-foot Athenian Venture, which was carrying gasoline from
Amsterdam to New York, apparently exploded and caught fire early
Friday.
   The Cypriot-registered tanker was owned by Patron Marine of
Athens.
   The recovered body, which was wearing a lifejacket, carried the
ship's logs. The logs gave no indication of what had happened on
the vessel.
   Rough seas and rain squalls hampered searchers Friday, but the
weather cleared overnight. Skies were overcast today, but winds
were calm, Terrill said.
   Terrill said the Hudson, the Canadian research vessel that first
spotted the burning tanker, will continue searching for possible
survivors today. A Canadian Forces patrol plane was scanning the
seas and would be rejoined by two American C130 Hercules from North
Carolina later today.
   Vessels using the shipping lane were being asked to be on the
lookout for the remaining 28 missing crewmembers.
</TEXT>
