<HEAD>Three Youths From Massachusetts Fined After Assault On Waiter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three college students from
Massachusetts have been fined a total of $1,300 for assaulting a
waiter at a Bermuda hotel after he told them to stop throwing doves
into a swimming pool.
   Arthur Anthony Guidara, of Boston, Gregory Patrick Long, and
Robert Thomas Norton, both of Dorchester, Mass., pleaded guilty to
assault and causing grievous bodily harm and were fined at a
magistrate court hearing on Thursday.
   The men, all 18, allegedly attacked waiter Edward Redman, 26,
and beat him unconscious at the Flamingo Beach Club on April 19.
   Redman had approached the three vacationing Americans after one
of them had thrown two caged doves into the hotel swimming pool.
   Redman, who is still recovering in the British colony's King
Edward VII Hospital, suffered a fractured cheekbone, damage to an
eye muscle and facial cuts which took 23 stitches to close.
   Redman said the sentences were lighter than many handed down for
traffic offenses. He claimed that his hospital bill is likely to be
higher than the fines. As a result of his injuries he wil have to
fly to Washington, D.C., next week for eye surgery.
   ``I was very saddened to hear details of a fine,'' Redman, said
from his hoptial bed today.
   Senior prosecutor Robin McMillan said, ``The beating was an
atrocious act.'' He said a short prison term would not be out of
place.
   The maximum penalty was a year in jail or fines of up to $1,500
each.
</TEXT>
