<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Solidarity     04-23 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Solidarity,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Solidarity Leaders Reported Detained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plainclothes police, seeking to prevent a
meeting of the outlawed trade federation Solidarity, have detained
three of its leaders, opposition activists said today.
   Jerzy Dluzyniewski, a member of Solidarity's National Executive
Commission, was arrested today at his house. Police told him he was
being detained 48 hours ``for his own good'' to prevent an illegal
meeting, said Joanna Onyszkiewicz, wife of Solidarity's national
spokesman, Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
   The other two detained leaders were Wladyslaw Frasyniuk and
Stefania Hajmanowska. They are also members of Solidarity's
Executive Commission, chaired by union leader and 1983 Nobel Peace
Prize laureate Lech Walesa.
   Frasyniuk was detained today, said Solidarity spokeswoman
Barbara Labuda in Wroclaw. Ms. Hajmanowska was detained Friday,
according to Zbigniew Romaszewski, a Solidarity leader in Warsaw
who monitors human rights cases.
   Walesa declined comment over the telephone from his home in
Gdansk about any plans for a meeting. Solidarity leaders presume
their phone conversations are monitored by police.
   Solidarity was declared illegal after Poland's 1981 martial law
crackdown, but its leadership has remained active, especially since
a 1986 political amnesty.
   Authorities frequently use fines and brief detentions to counter
union activities, but no lengthy jail sentences of senior union
leaders have been imposed since the amnesty.
   Meanwhile, police broke up an illegal printing operation in the
western copper-mining town of Glogow, Ms. Labuda said today.
   Printing equipment and some underground publications were
confiscated after a search of five private apartments that lasted
six hours, she said. The five Solidarity activists whose apartments
were searched were released but told they will likely face
misdemeanor charges.
</TEXT>
