<1ST_LINE>r a PM-O'Connor-Cuba     04-23 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O'Connor-Cuba,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Says Fidel Castro Wants Normal Relations With United
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fidel Castro praised nuns, the pope and showed
he ``definitely is reaching toward the church'' as he met for four
hours with Cardinal John J. O'Connor, the church leader says.
   O'Connor, the first Roman Catholic cardinal to visit Cuba since
Castro gained power in 1959, also said Castro indicated he would
release up to 350 political prisoners if the United States were to
give them visas.
   Castro asked for the church to see if it could play a role in
smoothing the way for arrangements, and O'Connor said he ``told him
we would be happy to do this.''
   And the Cuban leader also indicated he wants to restore normal
diplomatic relations with the United States, O'Connor said at a
news conference at LaGuardia Airport after he returned Friday from
his four-day trip.
   Officially, O'Connor went to Cuba as a guest of the Catholic
Church to celebrate the 200th anniversary of the birth of the Rev.
Felix Varela, who served in New York City from 1823 to 1853.
   When O'Connor asked Castro if he could clear the way for
Americans to visit sick relatives in Cuba, Castro said that would
be no problem at all, the cardinal said.
   At one point, O'Connor said he asked Castro for four more visas
for Mother Teresa's Missionary Sisters of Charity.
   ``The instant I proposed it, he expressed great delight and
granted (the visas) at that moment. He then went into great praise
of the nuns in Cuba. I've never heard nuns praised so highly,'' he
said.
   Castro also ``went into great praise of the pope and said he's
certainly the world leader in terms of peace and in terms of
constantly speaking about the poor,'' O'Connor said.
   ``I don't think there's any question that, for whatever motive,
he's beginning to feel the needs of the church,'' O'Connor said of
the Cuban president.
   Although Castro was friendly, O'Connor said he was ``thinking
all the time'' about whether the political figure was trying to
exploit him.
   At first during their talks, Castro ``gave me an extensive
tirade against the United States. He told me he has long since
learned to do without the United States,'' O'Connor said.
   But he said he later got the feeling that ``he (Castro) would be
delighted to re-establish a normal relationship'' with the United
States.
   O'Connor said he expected that normal relations would include a
resumption of trade and discussions at a diplomatic level as well
as ``within a very short period of time the free flow of people
going back and forth.''
   And the possibility of greater openness toward the church also
seemed a prospect in the Soviet Union, which is considering
allowing O'Connor to celebrate a Christmas Mass in Moscow to be
broadcast to a national audience, he said.
   The New York prelate first mentioned the proposal Thursday at a
news conference in Havana.
   The cardinal said he would prefer such a Mass on New Year's Day,
so he could continue the tradition of celebrating midnight
Christmas Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral.
   A televised Mass in the Soviet Union would be ``another move
toward building a bridge,'' O'Connor said. ``The bridge has to be
built. It may be a year. It may take a century.''
</TEXT>
