<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Blast 5thLd-Writethru a0507 04-23 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Blast, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0507,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb In Tripoli Kills 50</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to raise reference to crowded market and
include background on Ramadan.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A TNT-laden pickup truck exploded today
in a crowded vegetable market in the northern port city of Tripoli,
killing at least 50 people and wounding 80 others, police said.
   The 8:45 a.m. (2:45 a.m. EDT) explosion knocked down several
buildings, gutted shops and set fire to dozens of cars in the
low-income Tabbaneh district of Lebanon's second largest city, 50
miles north of Beirut.
   The explosion occurred as Moslem shoppers filled the market on
the seventh day of the holy month of Ramadan, when observing
Moslems fast during daylight hours.
   It was the worst car bombing in Lebanon in nearly three years.
   Police said the pickup, apparently used to transport vegetables,
had been loaded with about 220 pounds of TNT.
   No group has claimed responsibility for the bombing, and police
said they had no clue as to who was to blame.
   Civil defense teams dug through the rubble looking for trapped
people.
   ``It was a real massacre. Several pedestrians and vendors were
torn to pieces,'' said a police spokesman, who could not be
identified under standing regulations.
   He said Syrian troops in charge of Tripoli's security cordoned
off the blast area as ambulances with wailing sirens took
casualties to hospitals.
   Car bombs are a by-product of Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war
between Moslems and Christians. More than 100,000 people have been
killed since fighting broke out in 1975.
   A car bomb exploded outside an ice cream parlor in Tripoli on
June 29, 1985, killing 50 people and wounding 110 as they
celebrated the Fitr feast marking the end of Ramadan.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, condemned
today's car bombing as a ``barbaric atrocity.''
   ``All hands must team up to stop these executioners from
committing further such crimes,'' he said.
   The city has a predominantly Sunni population of 850,000.
   There have been four bombings in Beirut and Tripoli in the last
three months in which five people have been killed and 15 wounded.
But police said none of them involved a car rigged with explosives.
   At least 57 people were killed and 288 wounded in 16 car
bombings in Lebanon last year.
</TEXT>
