<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SeveredHeads     04-23 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Severed Heads,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severed Heads Found Where Gurkha Separatists Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The severed heads of two unidentified
people were found in the Darjeeling region, where Gurkha militants
have been campaigning for a separate homeland in eastern India.
   The United News of India said the heads were found Friday in
front of the office of the government-owned State Bank of India at
Sonada, 15 miles west of Darjeeling town.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but Gurkha
militants were blamed for two similar beheadings earlier this month.
   On April 6, the severed head of school principal Dileswar Rai
was found at the road crossing in Kalimpong. Rai had defied the
Gurkha call for a strike and kept his school open.
   The severed head of Nirmal Rai, a reporter for a local
newspaper, was found at the same place on April 12. The reporter,
not related to the principal, was accused of being a police
informer.
   The attack on the teacher was claimed by the Gurkhaland
Liberation Tigers, one of several Gurkha rebel groups. Police also
blamed Gurkha militants for the reporter's death.
   The Gurkhas, who are Indians of Nepalese descent, say they want
a state of their own to protect their culture, language and
tradition. The Darjeeling region now is part of Marxist-governed
West Bengal state.
   At least 275 people have since the Gurkhas began their homeland
campaign in April 1986.
</TEXT>
