<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-US     04-23 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US,0838</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Farmers Burn U.S. Flag, Car In Rally, Talks Stalemated</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers smashed and burned an American car, torched
boxes of U.S. oranges and set fire to a U.S. flag in a rally
Saturday protesting U.S. demands that Japan end its restrictions on
imported beef and oranges.
   The violence came as U.S. negotiators ended a week of meetings
on trade with no new agreements. A U.S. trade representative
Saturday left for the United States after failing to persuade Japan
to drop import quotas on citrus and beef.
   ``The two sides remain very far apart, said Michael B. Smith,
deputy representative. ``My own opinion is that we moved further
apart,'' he told a news conference at the American Embassy before
his departure.
   About 300 farmers chanted ``Down with U.S. demands'' while a man
jumped onto an American car and smashed its windows with a large
hammer.
   The farmers, wearing head bands saying ``Protect Japanese
agriculture'' in the rain, then piled boxes of U.S. oranges on the
car and set it on fire along with a large American flag.
   Three members of Japan's parliament, including former Vice
Minister of Agriculture Seishiro Eto, attended the rally in the
town of Kokonone in Kyushu in western Japan.
   Scenes of the demonstration were shown on evening television
news broadcasts.
   Kyodo News Service said the farmers destroying the U.S. car were
following the example of U.S. congressmen who smashed a tape
recorder made by Japan's Toshiba Corp. in July last year.
   The congressmen were protesting sales of high-technology milling
machines to the Soviet Union by a Toshiba subsidiary.
   Smith said the two sides differ on three important issues: Japan
wants a transition period before it fully opens its market; it
wants to negotiate the level of foreign access during the
transition; and, after the market is open, Japan wants new or
additional ``border measures'' such as tariffs to protect its
markets.
   Smith said Washington would agree to a transition period as long
as Japan reciprocates by significantly increasing foreign access to
its markets.
   Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Takashi Sato will
leave for Washington this week to continue the talks, he said.
   Japanese newspapers said Saturday the government has decided to
liberalize Japan's beef imports in three years and orange imports
in five years to help defuse trade friction with the United States,
its main ally and trading partner.
   In exchange, Japan would impose a surcharge on American beef and
allow imports to increase by about 15 percent a year, according to
the Mainichi Daily News.
   An increase in surcharges on oranges is prohibited under
international trade rules established by the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
   But Smith said import surcharges are out of the question. He
declined to say which points the two sides agreed on, saying the
whole package must be negotiated and ``today's numbers are
yesterday's history.''
   The two sides have been negotiating since Tuesday, trying to
reach agreement on a new package after the previous beef and
oranges agreement expired April 1.
   In another set of consultations, Japan asked the United States
to lift the penalty tariffs it imposed on Japanese color
televisions, calculators, computers and power drills over alleged
Japanese violations of an agreement on sales of computer chips, but
the United States refused, saying ``the sanctions will be lifted
once the arrangement is functioning as intended.''
   The two sides also held discussions on structural changes in
Japan's economy and Japanese demands that the United States reduce
its budget deficit and do more to stimulate its own economy.
   The biggest topic of the week turned out to be an item that was
not on the agenda _ a 312-107 vote by the U.S. House of
Representatives approving a comprehensive trade bill that
retaliates against Toshiba Corp.
   The move punishes Toshiba for a subsidiary's sale of sensitive
high technology equipment to the Soviet Union and gives the U.S.
Trade Representative more power in dealing with complaints of
unfair trade practices by foreign countries.
   A U.S. trade official said the timing of the vote was
coincidental and was not designed to send a special message to the
Japanese during the week of talks.
   International Trade and Industry Minister Hajime Tamura
protested the measure and called on President Reagan to veto the
bill.
   ``I suspect that the U.S. House of Representatives was guilty of
racial discrimination and anti-Japanese sentiment in passing the
trade bill,'' Japanese newspapers quoted him as saying.
   Allen Wallis, visiting U.S. undersecretary of state for economic
affairs, said Friday he assured Japan that Reagan would veto the
bill in its present form. The House can override the veto with a
two-thirds' vote.
   Last year Japan bought about $28 billion in U.S. exports, second
only to Canada, and the United States bought 38 percent of Japan's
exports, making it Japan's biggest trading partner, Wallis said.
</TEXT>
