<DOCNO> AP880423-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   04-23 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposing Forces Flex Muscles to Prepare for Afghan Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 Soviet trucks and
armored vehicles lumbered out of the capital at dawn Saturday for
Lowgar province, where Moslem guerrillas have stepped up attacks as
Moscow prepares its troops to withdraw.
   Many ground convoys and transport planes have been leaving Kabul
in recent days to resupply Soviet positions and the vulnerable
Afghan army, according to residents and Western diplomats.
   The Soviets agreed April 14 in Geneva to withdraw their
estimated 115,000 troops from Afghanistan more than eight years
after Moscow intervened to prop up the Marxist government. The
withdrawal is to begin May 15.
   But the agreement is far from a peace accord. Guerrilla
activities, including bombings in Kabul itself, have increased
since February with the approach of spring and the melting of snow
in the northern Hindu Kush and other mountain ranges.
   An alliance of seven Moslem guerrilla groups, whose headquarters
are across the Afghan-Pakistani frontier, rejected the Geneva
accord because it does not guarantee a cutoff of Soviet aid to
President Najib's Afghan government.
   The United States, according to officials in Washington, will
not halt its arms supplies to the guerrillas until the Soviets stop
supplying Najib's troops.
   Meanwhile, the Soviets are are preparing for an escalation of
guerrilla attacks in areas that will be the last to be vacated,
according to foreign analysts.
   Afghanistan's rugged geography has made it a nightmare for
foreign armies since Alexander the Great's short-lived conquest in
the fourth century.
   Soviet watchposts on the road around Kabul show signs of recent
fortification. There is fresh concrete and stonework around Soviet
sentry posts. Bunkers are newly draped with camouflage netting,
Western diplomats said.
   Kabul, hub of Soviet operations, is expected to be one of the
last two cities the Soviets leave before the final withdrawal
deadline of Feb. 15, 1989.
   The other is Mazar-e-Sharif, 40 miles south of the Soviet border
on a dusty plain along the Oxus River.
   During a tightly supervised seven-and-a-half hour visit arranged
by the Afghan government on Friday, several signs of Soviet
presence were visible there. Soviet army fuel trucks were parked
near 20 Afghan air force MIG-21 fighter planes at the airport, a
dozen Soviet soldiers went about their work, and storefronts showed
the Cyrillic lettering used by the Soviets.
   According to Western diplomats and Afghan officials, all
speaking on condition of anonymity, the Soviet pullout will
probably start at their most exposed positions. These include bases
near the Pakistani border.
   Meanwhile, the Soviets have plenty to worry about. According to
a report compiled by Western diplomats, 22 bombs exploded in Kabul
in March, compared with 10 in February. They included magnetic
bombs with timing devices that can be attached to vehicles, one
diplomat said.
   Other guerrilla activities in recent weeks included curtailing
movement on roads linking Kabul with other major cities, according
to the diplomat and residents.
   The diplomat said the guerrillas cut the road to Ghazni, 75
miles southwest of Kabul, on April 14. A reporter who flew over the
road a week later saw only a dozen vehicles on a normally
well-traveled section of the road.
   Lowgar province, which abuts the Kabul-Ghazni road, is ``very
insecure,'' one Western source said.
   Indeed, the Soviet convoy that headed there Saturday showed
signs of apprehension.
   It included eight T-62 tanks, at least a dozen armored personnel
carriers, a score or more of trucks loaded with coal, and about 10
trucks carrying communications gear.
   Many trucks had metal plates that covered the lower half of the
windshield on the driver's side and left only a brick-sized opening
on the passenger's side.
   The drivers, many of whom appeared to be teen-agers, wore
helmets and flak jackets.
   Some trucks were mounted with anti-aircraft guns. The guerrillas
do not have aircraft, so the guns would presumably be used to
attack their mountain positions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
