<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--OceanRescue     04-23 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ocean Rescue,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Islanders Rescued In Pacific After Drifting 29 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight Kiribati islanders adrift in a canoe for
29 days were rescued by an American tuna boat in the western
Pacific, but the survivors said a woman and child died during the
ordeal, according to a fishing industry official.
   Friday's rescue occurred some 1,100 miles from Kiribati, an
island nation once known as the Gilbert Islands, said August
Felando, president of the San Diego-based American Tuna Boat
Association.
   Louis Machado, master of the J.M. Martinac, reported the rescue
of the three women and five men, Felando said. The survivors were
taken abord the fishing boat and were headed for Ponape, part of
the Federated States of Micronesia.
   They told Machado that a 2-year-old child and 27-year-old woman
had died while they were adrift, said Felando.
   Those aboard the motorized canoe survived on rainwater and fresh
fish after the engine failed during a trip from one island in the
Kiribati chain to another, he said. The bodies of the dead woman
and child were thrown overboard, he said.
</TEXT>
