<DOCNO> AP880423-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HealthCare Bjt   04-23 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Care, Bjt,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Health Care Plan Could Be `Godsend'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill McFarland believes his rising medical claims
for a diabetic condition cost him his job, along with his company
health insurance, but today he has hope in a new state law that he
thinks will ``save myself and my family from potential financial
ruin.''
   Massachusetts' universal health care act was signed into law
last week by Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, a Democratic presidential
contender who has touted it as an example for the rest of the
country. The first-in-the-nation measure promises to make
affordable health insurance available to all residents, rich or
poor, working or unemployed, by 1992.
   McFarland, 53, knows something about health insurance. The job
he lost was as a chief fraud investigator for a major Massachusetts
insurance company, his employer of 13 years.
   While other factors may have been involved in his termination,
McFarland is convinced that the claims he filed for six $1,000
diabetes-related eye operations played a major role.
   And since he began working as a self-employed financial
consultant, McFarland has found himself ``effectively in a Catch-22
situation'' in trying to get health insurance because his diabetes
is considered a non-coverable, pre-existing condition.
   ``My efforts have indicated to me I couldn't even get (a policy)
that would cover diabetes, irrespective of the dollars of premium I
were able to pay,'' he said. ``In other words, I can get coverage
except for the coverage that I need.''
   Enter the Massachusetts universal health care plan, under which
by 1992, or possibly sooner, the state will broker pooled insurance
for small businesses and individuals which participants can buy
into on a sliding fee schedule based on their income.
   The details of what these plans will offer will be decided later
by the new state agency that will manage the system. But Catherine
Dunham, Dukakis' health policy adviser, said pre-existing
conditions will definitely be covered.
   ``This is really landmark legislation,'' McFarland said. ``It's
recognizing, in my judgment, that health care is a right, rather
than a privilege.''
   Dukakis says the four-year phase-in will cost the state $645.2
million, minus about $22.5 million in projected Medicaid
cost-cutting. But some estimates have run as high as $1.2 billion.
   The law would extend coverage to about 600,000 Massachusetts
residents under age 65 currently without health insurance, or
roughly one of every 10 people in the commonwealth.
   This would be done in stages and through a variety of
approaches, from extending Medicaid benefits for disabled adults
and children to state- brokered, pooled insurance for small
businesses and individuals.
   By 1992, all employers with more than five full-time employees
must offer health insurance coverage or pay an unemployment
surcharge to help the state provide this coverage to the uninsured.
   Jeannette Capone, 52, lives in Athol with her healthy
14-year-old daughter and her 68-year-old husband, who has chronic
emphysema and hasn't been able to work for a dozen years.
   When her family was younger and she had five children living at
home, Capone briefly went on welfare. But she hated the
condescension she felt from neighbors and welfare workers so she
found work in part-time jobs that would allow her to continue
caring for her homebound husband.
   Today, Capone does light cleaning for a company that recently
began offering health insurance to full-time employees. But Capone
isn't covered because she only works about 20 hours a week.
   Capone gets free indigent medical care for herself and her
daughter through her local hospital's emergency room.
   Her husband's major medical expenses are covered by Medicare,
but she still has to pay for the seven medications he has to take,
costing $40 to $45 a week.
   ``What breaks me up is that I can apply for welfare, I can apply
for Medicaid'' and all her medical expenses will be paid, she said.
But to be eligible, she would have to quit her job.
   ``I want to work, I want to help and do things on my own,'' she
said.
   The state this year will allow disabled adults like her husband
to buy into the Medicaid program according to their ability to pay.
   And in 1992, most employers will be required to offer health
insurance to employees working at least 20 hours per week.
</TEXT>
