<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HealthCare-Glance     04-23 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Care-Glance,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Health Care Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of Massachusetts' universal
health care law to make affordable insurance available to all
residents by 1992. About 600,000 residents, roughly one of 10
people in the state, are uninsured.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>STATE COST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Gov. Michael S. Dukakis says the four-year phase-in will cost
the state $645.2 million, minus about $22.5 million in projected
Medicaid cost-cutting. But some estimates have run as high as $1.2
billion.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ADMINISTRATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A Department of Medical Security will be created to:
   _Manage hospitals' indigent care pools
   _Develop a program of supplemental health insurance for disabled
adults and children.
   _Oversee state-brokered pooled insurance for uninsured
individuals and businesses with up to six full-time employees.
   _Set up a sliding fee schedule based on ability to pay for
participants in supplemental and individual pooled state plans.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSINESS MANDATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Most employers must provide health insurance to employees by
Jan. 1, 1992, or pay an unemployment surcharge equal to 12 percent
of the first $14,000 of an employee's wages, or $1,680 per worker.
To avoid surcharge, an employer must offer a health plan in which
the employer's contribution is at least $1,680 per employee.
   _Employer coverage must be offered to full-time employees
working at least 30 hours per week and part-time employees working
at least 20 hours per week.
   _Any business with less than six employees is exempt.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSINESS INCENTIVES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Any business not offering employee health insurance previously
would be able to take an income and excise tax credit the first
year equaling 20 percent of health insurance premium; 10 percent
the second year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COVERAGE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Specific coverage requirements of employers will be decided by
the new department. But the plans must contain basic coverages
required of all health policies under state law _ in-patient and
out-patient acute hospital and physician services, diagnostic and
screening tests, preventive care, prenatal and well-baby care and
medically necessary emergency health services.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COLLEGES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _All colleges and universities must provide health insurance for
full-time students by Sept. 1, 1989.
</TEXT>
