<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--FishKill     04-23 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Fish Kill,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sewage Treatment Rupture Causes Massive Fish Kill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENOA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tons of fish along a 20-mile stretch of river
died when a pipe at a sewage treatment lagoon ruptured, sending an
estimated 400,000 gallons of toxic wastes cascading into the South
Branch Kishwaukee River.
   Jack Adam, environmental protection specialist with the Illinois
Environmental Protection Agency in Rockford, said the fish kill had
spread 20 miles from its source and nearly reached the Rock River.
   ``It's a pretty extensive fish kill, one of the worst we've seen
in many years,'' Adam said. ``It's a 100 percent kill for the first
10 miles of the river. I imagine there's hundreds of tons of dead
fish.''
   Adam said the kill occurred Wednesday night when employees at a
hog farm were installing new pipe in a dike on a sewage treatment
lagoon about two miles southwest of Genoa in northern Illinois.
   ``It's just got away from them,'' he said.
   No drinking water was threatened, Adam said.
</TEXT>
