<DOCNO> AP880423-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     04-23 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Admits Clashes with Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
acknowledged Saturday he had many differences in his talks with
General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev, but he tried to minimize
the disagreements.
   Gorbachev, speaking with Shultz, had made a scathing attack on
the ``sermons'' he said President Reagan and other U.S. officials
had delivered about Soviet behavior.
   The Soviet news agency Tass, in a dispatch distributed Friday
after Shultz ended two days of talks in Moscow, quoted Gorbachev as
telling Shultz that U.S.-Soviet relations ``are in need of a
drastic restructuring.''
   Gorbachev complained that ``everything that has been achieved in
Soviet-American relations is being ascribed to the policy of
strength and putting pressure on the Soviets.''
   He accused U.S. officials of constantly barraging their Soviet
counterparts with ``demands, terms and grievances'' about human
rights in the Soviet Union. ``We are not going to re-educate the
United States and do not recognize it has any right to re-educate
us,'' Gorbachev told Shultz.
   The Soviet leader was most distressed with a speech in
Springfield, Mass., on Thursday in which Reagan complained about
Soviet aggression worldwide. Reagan said that until it ended, ``the
world cannot know true peace.''
   Shultz, on a sightseeing tour of Kiev, the capital of the
Ukraine, said the superpowers have had ``lots of difficulties as
well as lots of accomplishments.''
   ``There have been some very tough parts to every meeting on both
sides,'' Shultz said. ``He has things to say. I have things to say,
and there are always some informative parts and there are positive
parts.''
   Later, flying from Kiev to Tbilisi, the capital of the Soviet
republic of Georgia, Shultz and other U.S. officials sought again
to convince reporters that Gorbachev's statement did not represent
new strains with the United States.
   As if to underscore that the dialogue will continue, Charles E.
Redman, the State Department spokesman, announced that Shultz would
meet with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze in Geneva
May 11-12 to continue preparations for Reagan's summit with
Gorbachev in Moscow May 29-June 2.
   Shultz called the Tass account and stories based on it
``overblown,'' and he defended Reagan's tough rhetoric.
   ``I think perhaps there is an overreaction to the Springfield
speech,'' Shultz said.
   ``The president has always taken the view, that I agree with,
that we have to state our views realistically all the time. And we
have to act in terms of the things we think need to be done.''
   Shultz said he would keep stressing a need to improve human
rights conditions in the Soviet Union.
   Little progress was reported on the focus of Shultz's talks in
Moscow, negotiating a treaty to cut in half the superpowers'
arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons.
   Shultz visited Kiev and Tbilisi for sightseeing before heading
Sunday for Brussels to brief the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
on his Moscow talks.
   In Kiev, the Ukrainian capital, he visited the site of a World
War II German atrocity.
   ``We have to say to ourselves always, never again,'' Shultz
declared in tribute to the 30,000 Jews and 70,000 other Ukrainians
the German invaders herded into a ravine at Babi Yar and
machine-gunned in September 1941.
   Stressing the heavy Jewish toll, Shultz said, ``This was among
the first places where we saw the holocaust and the slaughter of
Jews.''
   His visit fell on the Jewish Sabbath. Shultz laid a wreath at a
monument the Soviets erected in 1976 and observed a minute of
silence.
   The American envoy also visited an unfinished U.S. consulate in
Kiev, the third largest city in the Soviet Union. Construction of
the mission has been halted and no date has been set for completion.
   American officials cite security concerns, a tighter budget and
congressional opposition. But Shultz favors opening the consulate
for the wider knowledge it would bring of the Soviet Union.
   ``Our plan if we move ahead is to have what we call an
unclassified post,'' staffed by five or six Americans, he said.
   The idea is not to have any sensitive material in the consulate
and thereby not make it a target for Soviet eavesdropping.
</TEXT>
