<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ElevatorExplosion 3rdLd-Writethru a0540 04-23 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elevator Explosion, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0540,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Search for Missing in Elevator Explosions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead; SUBS 8th graf, `As many ...,' with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with diving canceled by choppy water.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 rescue workers combed the wreckage
of a grain elevator complex today for two of three men missing
after an explosion leveled the facility, while boats dragged a
river alongside the granary for a third man, authorities said.
   Friday's explosion killed two other workers at the ADM Growmark
complex, and authorities said there was only a ``very small''
chance the three missing men were alive.
   Three others were injured in the fiery blasts.
   By morning, workers using bulldozers and cranes had cleared the
site of about 50 percent of the twisted metal, chunks of concrete
and piles of corn and soybeans left strewn over the site by the
explosion, said an official at the disaster command post who would
not identify himself.
   Dogs were used to sniff through the grain piles but had found no
sign of the missing men. Workers remained cautiously hopeful today
that they might still be alive, the official said.
   ``It would be very small, but yes of course, there is hope,'' he
said.
   Authorities believe the two blasts, which leveled grain silos
and an office building, may have been sparked by ignited grain dust.
   As many as six boats dragged the Des Plaines River for the body
of the third missing man, who was believed to have been thrown off
a barge by the force of the explosions, and four divers searched
downstream Friday, authorities said.
   Boats continued the search today, but winds and choppy water
kept divers out of the water, authorities said.
   A gnarled life jacket was found in the river, but there was no
sign of the missing man, Romeoville Fire Department Capt. John
Ramos said.
   The fiery blasts likened by witnesses to results of dynamite or
a tornado ripped through the ADM Growmark complex along the river
about 40 miles southwest of Chicago late Friday morning, officials
said.
   Authorities identified the dead as Dale Brent Slatton, 28, of
Newark, Ill. and Mark D. Stewart, 20, of Anchor. Both worked at the
elevator, Stewart part time while he studied agriculture at Joliet
Junior College.
   Joliet Police Sgt. David Saxon identified the missing as Michael
Dupris, 23, of Bourbonnais, Daniel McLaughlin, 18, of Manhattan,
Ill., and Don Zack, 30, of Joliet.
   The explosions shattered windows in homes east of the elevator
complex and sprayed grain and rubble, burying a tractor-trailer rig.
   ``I thought it sounded like a tornado or something,'' said Bob
Butterfield, 64, a Wilmington farmer who witnessed the blast. ``I
started running, but I was knocked down.''
   He said he was rolling on the ground when he saw the four,
100-foot concrete silos falling.
   ``It was falling straight down like it had disintegrated,'' he
said. ``It's gone, totaled, level complete _ just like dynamite.''
   Authorities suspect grain dust may have caused the first
explosion, which apparently ruptured a natural gas main about 11
a.m. and touched off a second blast moments later, said Joliet Fire
Chief George Plese.
   ``Fairly heavy levels of dust, almost like a dense fog,'' would
have had to accumulate to set off such a powerful blast, said Ralph
Regan, a safety manager with the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   Joliet Fire Batallion Chief Richard Colbert said the dust can be
``highly volatile, like petroleum.''
   David Munchalfen, a security guard at the facility, said there
had been four silos at the site, and only a sheet-metal covered
grain dryer remained standing. One of the silos, each of which
could hold about 100,000 bushels, crushed the adjacent one-story
office building.
   Bill Contos, 26, of Joliet, a boat pilot working near the
elevator site, said the second blast was ``just like a big ball of
flame the whole length of the elevator.''
   Two people were taken to St. Joseph Medical Center. One of them,
James Rayburn, 40, of Papineau was in fair condition, while the
second man was released, said spokeswoman Phyllis Oudt.
   A third injured worker was treated and released from Silver
Cross Hospital, said spokeswoman Julie Grant.
</TEXT>
