<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru   04-23 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0548,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Unsure Of Jackson's Interest In Sharing Democratic Ticket</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with Dukakis speech; picks up
9th graf pvs, bgng: Dukakis recalls...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede PHILADELPHIA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis
said Saturday he's not sure Jesse Jackson is even interested in the
No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket, adding that he and Jesse
Jackson have ``one overriding goal'' _ a Democratic victory in
November.
   The Massachusetts governor continued to take shots at the Reagan
administration on a variety of issues, testing themes for the fall
campaign now that he has moved into a commanding position in the
Democratic nomination fight.
   Foreign policy and Attorney General Edwin Meese's problems at
the Justice Department were his targets for Saturday.
   ``I'm not here to beat up on the current administration _ they
have have enough problems _ and the Justice Department especially
these days, if there is a Justice Department,'' Dukakis told about
300 people at the old Bethlehem Steel headquarters in the Lehigh
Valley.
   Dukakis campaigned hard across Pennsylvania in preparation for
Tuesday's primary. He also made a quick trip to Gary, Ind., in
advance of that state's May 3 balloting.
   Dukakis and Jackson faced each other in a second debate in as
many days in Pittsburgh Saturday night.
   At the Bethlehem event, Dukakis was asked about Jackson's
interest in the vice presidential nomination.
   ``That is not what he said. I asked him if he were interested
but he didn't tell me,'' Dukakis said of an exchange they had in
the Friday night debate in Philadelphia.
   ``As you could see last night, Jesse and I have a very good
relationship. We respect each other,'' Dukakis said .``We happen to
be very positive people. We both understand that there is one
overriding goal in this campaign and that is to win in November.''
   Dukakis has a big lead in the polls in Pennsylvania, which has a
beauty contest primary and separate elections for national
convention delegates.
   ``Every single primary is important. Please don't pay any
attention to the polls,'' he told the union members. ``We need a
big turnout. Everybody has to vote. And you have to vote not only
for me but for my delegates.''
   Dukakis began his day standing in front of the freighter
Tradewind at dockside in North Philadelphia, talking of
federal-local partnerships when music suddenly blared.
   ``What have we got here, a symphony behind me?'' said the
Massachusetts governor, turning toward the ship.
   Then he noticed the Greek flag being waved from the ship's
bridge.
   ``We're going to have a brief pause while we all appreciate
this,'' which he said sounded like a Greek battle hymn from the
Revolution fo 1821. ``This is too much.''
   The Greek-American politician is a far more relaxed campaigner
now that he has opened a big lead over Jackson. He mixes pleas for
a big turnout Tuesday with themes that he would use as the party's
nominee in the fall.
   ``We're going to take back the presidency for the Democratic
Party and for the country in November. It's out there to be won.
The people of this countryare ready for a change. You know and I
know. We hear it every day,'' Dukakis told about 100 people at a
Machinists Union hall, his second stop Saturday morning. ``They
want an Attorney General we can be proud of, not an Atorney General
we're embarrassed about.''
   Dukakis recalls his upset in the 1978 Democratic primary _ when
he as the incumbent lost to a lesser-know conservative candidate
after leading by 50 points in the polls.
   ``We were all looking at our statistics and we weren't
remembering that it's out on the ballfield where you have to win
that game,'' he said.
   As he has in recent days since his major New York vicory last
Tuesday, Dukakis have emphasized the tone he wants to set in the
campaign, a theme those who appear with him have adopted.
   ``He's going to take the high road all the way to Atlanta and
all the way to the White House,'' said Rep. Bob Borski, D-Pa.,
introducing Dukakis at the union hall.
   In particuarly, Dukakis rejects any suggestion of criticism of
Jackson.
   ``It's important that we run a strong and positive campaign,''
Dukakis said. ``I don't think the American people are interested in
what I think of Jesse Jackson or what he thinks of me. They want to
know what kind of leadership we're going to provide for this
country. They want to know whether I have the strenght, the values,
the experience and and the ability to lead this country''
   He has also been working on how to include his cousin Olympia _
who won an Oscar for best supporting actress two weeks ago _ in his
stump speech.
   ``This has been an incredible two weeks for the Dukakis
family...Who else but my cousin would hold up that Oscar in front
of a billion and half of people and say `Okay, Michael let's go.'
   ``That's our cry _ `Let's go'.'' ~
</TEXT>
