<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0578 04-23 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0578,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Warns Iran Against Continued Military, Terrorist Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf, But the, to make clear that Monday action was
taken under old policy; INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf, `We have,'
with Aspin comments; DELETES last graf to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan warned Iran's leaders
Saturday that continued attacks on neutral countries and refusal to
negotiate an end to the Persian Gulf war ``will be very costly to
Iran and its people.''
   The president, in his weekly radio address delivered from Camp
David, Md., said, ``We do not seek to confront Iran.''
   But, he said, Iran's ``leaders must understand that continued
military and terrorist attacks against non-belligerents and refusal
to negotiate an end to the war will be very costly to Iran and its
people.''
   Reagan's tough comments came a day after administration
officials let it be known that under a new policy, the United
States will allow American warships to assist neutral vessels under
attack in the gulf.
   The United States, while remaining officially neutral in the
7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war, has guarded American-flagged Kuwaiti
tankers from attack since last summer.
   But the escort policy was expanded to allow U.S. warships to aid
neutral merchant ships under attack after the U.S. frigate Roberts
struck a mine in the gulf on April 14. Under the old rules, which
permitted retaliation only for attacks on American-flagged ships,
U.S. forces retaliated last Monday, sinking or crippling six
Iranian vessels that challenged them after the Americans destroyed
two offshore platforms.
   ``The actions that our forces took in the gulf were a measured
response to Iran's resumption of mine laying and continued
aggression against non-belligerents,'' the president said.
   ``We have completed these self-defense actions and consider this
incident closed.''
   In a statement on the gulf Saturday, Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, said that the
United States must face the issue of whether an intelligence
failure was involved in the Iranian mine-laying incident.
   ``Iran's minelayers have clearly found a large hole in our
procedures _ a hole large enough to drive at least two minefields
through,'' he said. ``We have to assume, for planning purposes,
that more minefields have already been laid, and we also have to
assume that more minefields will now be laid.''
   Aspin had said earlier that he suspected the mines were not laid
on orders from the Tehran government, but by revolutionary
malcontents. ``Regardless of who in Iran ordered the minelaying, we
are back to a state of confrontation,'' he said Saturday.
   The president, in his radio speech, said that he is ``extremely
proud of the courage and resourcefulness of our military personnel
in the Persian Gulf. Their performance under very difficult
circumstances has been superb.
   ``We are also very pleased with the role that the European
allies are playing in a cooperative effort to counter the Iranian
mining threat and to help protect freedom of navigation. Such
cooperative efforts, supported by our gulf Arab friends, offer the
best means of deterring Iran and enhancing gulf security.''
   ``Working together, we can also put new life into the U.N.
Security Council's efforts to end the increasingly bloody, inhumane
Iran-Iraq war and remove the root cause of tensions in the gulf,''
Reagan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
