<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrisisCenter     04-23 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crisis Center,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama May Be First State To Get `Survivable' Shelter For
Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NEWBERRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alabama has been chosen as the site for
the nation's first survivable state emergency operating center, a
disaster-proof shelter designed to allow state government to keep
running even during a nuclear attack.
   ``Many EOC's date back to the 1950s,'' said Bill McAda, a
spokesman for the Federal Emergency Management Agency. ``We're
looking for a modern approach to civil defense.''
   If funding is approved by the state Legislature, the facility
would provide safe haven for the governor and other top officials
to direct evacuation procedures and other emergency operations
during a nuclear attack.
   ``The population would be in disarray,'' said J. Danny Cooper,
director of the state Emergency Management Agency. ``They would be
confused and afraid. ... They would have confidence in those they
have placed in high public office.''
   The federal agency chose Alabama to receive $1.1 million in
funding to build the center, but only if Alabama provides matching
funds. Cooper said the state was chosen based on its letter of
intent guaranteeing the center would provide for the number of
state officials and personnel needed to coordinate disaster
operations and resources.
   Cooper said recently that the facility has not yet been
designed, but it would have to be a subterranean, windowless
facility capable of accommodating as many as 270 members of state
government ``necessary to ensure a return to normalcy.'' That would
include the governor, top Cabinet officials, legislative leaders
and judges.
   Walls several feet thick would protect inhabitants from
radioactivity and a ventilation system would filter the air. Wells
would be dug to provide an adequate water supply for at least two
weeks.
   ``It would not be the Grand Hotel,'' said Cooper, referring to
an exclusive resort on Mobile Bay. ``It would provide food,
clothing and shelter.''
   More importantly, Cooper said, would be the center's
state-of-the-art communications capability, including retractable
antennas and equipment that would be functional even under
radioactive conditions. Such technology already is in place at
federal facilities.
   ``During a nuclear exchange, the atmosphere would eliminate
radio communications,'' he said. ``Our facility would be the
national model of a communications system that can function
regardless of the situation.''
   In addition to a nuclear attack, the center could be used during
hurricanes, tornadoes or any other natural or technological
disaster, such as a crisis at the state's two nuclear power plants.
   McAda said most states have some kind of emergency operations
center, but FEMA determined in a recent study that their
capabilities were ``low and declining.''
   ``The continuity of government concept is one that FEMA will be
pursuing very vigorously in the future,'' said Cooper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
