<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1503EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras     04-23 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Crippled By Submission To US, Politicians and Diplomats
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians and diplomats say
President Jose Azcona's already weak government has been crippled
because of its apparent inability to stand up to the United States.
   Interviews with prominent Hondurans, as well as talks with
foreign envoys and people in the street, indicated that citizens of
this old friend of the United States are peeved with what they see
as Yankee high-handedness.
   Local politicians said a series of events have prompted a
fundamental review of U.S.-Honduran relations, which they said
probably will change definitively, if not drastically.
   In recent days, Hondurans have bristled at the transportation of
a Honduran national to the United States on cocaine charges, done
even though the Honduran Constitution prohibts extradition of
Honduran citizens.
   Many are angry about the use of Honduran territory by the
U.S.-backed Contra rebels in their fight against the Nicarguan
government.
   And the maneuvers of 3,200 American troops in Honduras last
month were also seen by many as another example of U.S. dominance.
   Even a presidential decision Monday to award a
multimillion-dollar compensation to a U.S. citizen whose farm was
expropriated in 1982 has incurred the people's wrath.
   ``Yankee garbage out of Honduras,'' and ``If the Yankees don't
get out, in Honduras they will die,'' about 2,000 people chanted as
they marched in the capital Thursday.
   The chants, which rhyme in Spanish, would have sounded foreign
on so many voices just a few months ago.
   The march came two weeks after a mob sacked and burned the U.S.
Consulate.
   The demonstrators, like others, say Azcona's submission to U.S.
wishes in recent months has reached the point where Honduran
insitutions, including the Constitution, are blatantly ignored.
   Despite the ire of the students who made up the core of the
marchers, most Hondurans are far from anti-American. Those
consulted last week seemed especially hurt because the perceived
slights are coming from a friend.
   ``Matta as an individual has no importance. He was just a
detonator,'' said Manuel Acosta Bonilla, a lawyer and member of the
directorate of the opposition National Party.
   He was referring to Juan Ramon Matta, who was arrested April 5
and hustled out of the country and into the federal penetentiary in
Marion, Ill., by Honduran authorities working closely with U.S.
officials.
   Matta, considered an international cocaine kingpin, was one of
the U.S. Druge Enforcement Agency's most wanted men.
   ``If they can kidnap Matta, they can kidnap anybody's brother,''
said truck driver Marcos Lezama. ``The servileness of this
president has no name.''
   ``There is complete indignation because of poor management of
this (Matta) situation,'' said Carlos Montoya, president of
Congress and a presidential hopeful for Azcona's Liberal Party in
fall 1989 elections.
   ``The image of Azcona has been eroded,'' he said. But Montoya
said he doesn't think a military coup is possible.
   ``The U.S. Congress would cut off aid, and the economic
situation here would go from bad to worse,'' he said.
   The armed forces governed Honduras for nearly 20 years before a
return to civilian rule in 1982. The military still continues to
exercise much political power.
   Honduras is one of the poorest countries in the hemisphere, with
50 percent unemployment or underemployment, 60 percent illiteracy
and a per capita annual gross national product of just over $750.
   Gilberto Goldstein, a National Party legislator, agreed that a
coup was almost out of the question ``because everyone involved
would lose.''
   He said these are trying times for what had until a few months
ago been an island of relative tranquility amid Central America's
turmoil.
   ``But some good comes out of this,'' he said. ``It will make the
United States realize its relations with Honduras must be
profoundly reanalyzed.''
   According to Acosta Bonilla, ``It doesn't matter that the small
left takes up this banner of resentment. But it (the resentment)
will consolidate the broader center-left for a revision of the
status quo.''
   Meza said the presidential candidate who taps into this
resentment will have an advantage.
   ``Our presidential campaign is virtually underway,'' he said,
``and no one who hopes to win can fail to take this resentment into
account.''
</TEXT>
