<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites SUB a0591 04-23 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, SUB, a0591,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Corrects this week to last week in graf 4, ``Capacity crowds
xxx; Evangel cq in same graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The devil had better think twice about
wrestling with the five Assemblies of God ministers known as The
Power Team.
   These preachers crash chest-first through stacks of 2-by-4's,
break free of handcuffs and bend 1-inch steel rods between their
teeth _ all in the name of the Lord.
   ``If I walk into an auditorium in a suit and tie, probably
nobody would notice or listen,'' John Jacobs, the team founder,
told a crowd in Louisville last week. ``But if I break ice, crush
concrete and break out of handcuffs, it gets people's attention.''
   Capacity crowds of 3,000 screaming, cheering people showed up at
the Evangel Christian Life Center several nights last week to see
the team, which is made up of former professional athletes who all
are in their 20s.
   ``Tonight is for radicals only,'' Jacobs told one crowd. ``Men
pushing their bodies to the limit. But most important, they love
God. So, fasten your seat belts.''
   Jacobs, who weighs more than 300 pounds and has 21-inch biceps,
showed his stuff by freeing himself from two pairs of handcuffs.
Former Indiana University football star Berry Handley crashed
chest-first through a stack of 2-by-4's.
   And former Seattle Seahawks running back Mike Hagen, who boasts
of a 54-inch chest, crushed two 5-foot-thick slabs of ice with his
triceps.
   Team members competed to see which one would be first to blow up
a thick rubber hot-water bottle until it burst, bend a 1-inch steel
rod between his teeth and then snap a baseball bat across his knees.
   ``Hollywood has always shown Christians as sissies,'' Jacobs
said, ``but it takes more courage to live for God than anything
else in the world. Jesus was a real man.''
</TEXT>
