<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Delvalle-Panama     04-23 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delvalle-Panama,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hidden President Says Noriega May Want U.S. Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Panamanian President Eric Arturo
Delvalle said in an interview broadcast Saturday that military
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega ``is not sound of mind'' and may
want a U.S. invasion of his country.
   ``Maybe he believes that (an invasion) will be an honorable way
out,'' Delvalle said in a videotaped interview on Cable News
Network's ``Newsmaker Saturday.'' The network said the interview
was taped Monday at an undisclosed location in Panama.
   ``He doesn't know what he wants. He just want to hold off and
prove that he can hold off an American invasion. ... Noriega is not
sound of mind,'' said Delvalle, who called for either a Panamanian
military uprising or an international military force to oust
Noriega.
   Delvalle, who tried to fire Noriega as military commander two
months ago and then was ousted himself by Panama's
Noriega-controlled legislature, said he would remain in the
country. He said he has been staying in the houses of six different
Panamanian families.
   But Delvalle, who is recognized as Panama's president by the
U.S. government, acknowledged little support in the streets of
Panama for toppling Noriega and called for people to sacrifice.
   ``We are sinking the ship to grab the captain,'' he said. ``We
know that.''
   Delvalle said Panamanians have not risen up against Noriega
because they are afraid of him.
   ``They're terrorized. They've got beaten. They don't dare go out
to the streets and protest,'' he said.
   Delvalle said Noriega, who is accused in U.S. courts of drug
trafficking, is backed by Cubans, Nicaraguans, the Colombia-based
Medellin drug cartel and other Panamanian military officers who
will have to be kicked out with him.
   The president-in-hiding said he doubted that Noriega would wage
a guerrilla war if he is finally forced out of office, because he
hasn't got that kind of support and ``I think he's too rich to do
any of that type of foolish action.''
   U.S. officials allege that Noriega has made millions of dollars
by supporting illegal drug operations.
</TEXT>
