<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ElSalvador     04-23 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-El Salvador,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Threaten New Mayors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas battling the
U.S.-backed government said Saturday they will prevent newly
elected mayors from taking office and cited their recent
assassination of one mayor.
   A message broadcast by the rebels' Radio Venceremos began with
``A call to all mayors'' in which the guerrillas said: ``The FMLN
will not permit you to exercise your functions.
   ``We warn that mayors will have to resign their posts or abandon
their towns. We will be strict in enforcing this measure,'' the
radio said.
   The FMLN is the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, an
alliance of five guerrilla groups waging an 8-year-old campaign
against U.S.-backed forces.
   The radio referred to the April 15 slaying by guerrillas of
Pedro Ventura, mayor-elect of the eastern town of San Isidro.
   It said he was killed ``because he refused to withdraw. He had
been warned.''
   Ventura represented the rightist party Arena, which won
two-thirds of the country's 262 mayoralties in March 20 legislative
and municipal elections.
   The threat came a day after the Supreme Court admitted a writ
filed by Arena, charging the incumbent Christian Democrats with
fraud in counting votes for national legislators from the eastern
province of La Union.
   The court did not say when it would rule definitively. But it
suspended certification of the disputed legislator from the
province, which means Arena will have an outright majority when the
new Legislative Assembly is installed May 1.
   Arena has 30 seats assured in the 60-seat legislature, which
because of the suspension will have only 59 members until the La
Union case is resolved.
   The count disputed by Arena gave two of La Union's three
legislators to the Christian Democrats. Arena claims it won two of
the three.
   The disputed count gave Arena a total of 30 deputies, the
Christian Democrats 23 and the National Conciliation Party seven.
   But until the case is resolved, the Christian Democrats, who
have formed an informal alliance with the Conciliation Party, will
have 22 seats.
   An Arena-controlled legislature is expected to make President
Jose Napoleon Duarte's last year in office an uphill struggle.
Duarte is a Christian Democrat.
</TEXT>
