<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Religion     04-23 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Religion,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underground Preacher Reportedly Arrested Trying to See Billy
Graham</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An underground preacher who spreads Christian
gospel in China was arrested in a Beijing park after he came to
hear U.S. evangelist Billy Graham, a religious rights activist said
Saturday.
   Xu Yongzhe, from China's central Henan province, was detained
April 16, one day before Graham preached to more than 1,500 people
in a Beijing church, said Jonathan Chao, director of the Chinese
Church Research Center.
   Graham was in Shanghai on Saturday as part of his two-week tour
of China and could not immediately be reached for comment.
   Chao described Xu as an itinerant evangelist who trains his
followers to conduct preaching services and establish new
non-denominational churches.
   Since 1980, Xu's team of evangelists has established more than
3,000 local churches that are loosely associated, Chao said. His
claim could not be independently verified.
   Chao's center is known in Hong Kong for having critical views of
the Chinese government.
   China permits freedom of religion but religious activity is
closely monitored by the state. Proselytizing to the general public
is banned, but preaching in the state churches is allowed.
   There are 4,000 state-sanctioned churches in China. The official
Patriotic Catholic Church, which split with the Vatican in the
1950s, claims more than 3 million members throughout China. An
unknown number of other Chinese remain loyal to the pope.
   China also says it has several million Protestants.
   Xu worked outside the state-sanctioned churches because if he
worked with the state he would have been ``forbidden to expand the
Christian faith by preaching,'' Chao said.
   Chao said Xu was arrested in 1982 for preaching and was put in a
detention center for several years.
   Xu has since worked clandestinely in the countryside of central
China spreading the gospel, Chao claimed.
   Chao said he was informed of Xu's arrest in a letter dated April
20 from reliable Christian sources inside China. There was no way
to independently confirm the information and authorities in Beijing
were unavailable for comment this afternoon.
   According to the four-page letter, Xu told a friend in Beijing
that he would come to the capital to see Graham. Chao believes the
letter was intercepted by authorities.
   Xu arrived in Beijing on April 13 and was arrested three days
later while walking in Yuetan park with friends, the letter says.
   ``He was arrested because he wanted to hear Billy Graham
preach,'' said Chao.
   Chao said he had no further updates on Xu's situation.
   Chao said his center publishes a weekly news report and a
monthly magazine about religion in China. He described himself as
being critical of the religious policies of China which he said
persecutes itinerant preachers.
</TEXT>
