<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     04-23 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Election Violence Leave Dozens Injured; Police Guard Rallies
Nationwide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Street clashes between members of
rival parties left dozens injured Saturday, and police guarded
scores of rallies leading up to this week's elections, police and
newspapers reported.
   A neighborhood leader in Seoul died Saturday after he was
injured in a fight Friday over how to distribute gift towels from a
governing party candidate to voters, one newspaper reported.
   Opposition politicians said the case showed irregular campaign
methods by the Democratic Justice Party.
   Major local newspapers said their surveys indicated the
governing Democratic Justice Party was likely to win a majority
Tuesday in the 299-seat National Assembly. That would strengthen
the position of President Roh Tae-woo, who won office in December
with just 36 percent of the vote.
   Police said ``all available police forces'' were mobilized to
watch 148 campaign rallies Saturday. The Korean news agency,
Yonhap, reported the rallies were largely peaceful because of the
heavy security.
   At some rallies, police in full riot gear lined up three or four
deep along one side of the podium.
   A dozen people were injured overnight when students armed with
firebombs attacked a governing party office in the southern city of
Chonju and a nearby police station.
   In the central city of Taejon, a campaign minibus covered with
opposition party posters was set on fire overnight, and gangs
attacked opposition party supporters in some rural areas on
Saturday.
   Once again, the opposition is split and the surveys showed
governing party candidates leading for more than 90 of the seats
being decided in 224 districts. Seventy-five other seats are being
decided by nationwide vote proportions, with the leading party
predicted to win 38 of them.
   The last assembly had 276 seats, with 160 held by the Democratic
Justice Party.
   In Tuesday's voting, 1,045 candidates are competing for the 224
district seats. The winners will serve for four years, compared
with a five-year term for the president, who is limited to one term.
   In a news conference Saturday, opposition leader Kim Young-sam
contended that ``our country will enter a gloomy period if the
ruling party, controlled by tycoons, generals and corrupt
bureaucrats, wins a majority.''
   Rival opposition leader Kim Dae-jung warned that the Roh
government would face popular outbursts if it continued the
allegedly improper campaigning.
   In December, both Kim Dae-jung and Kim Young-sam insisted on
running for president, splitting the opposition vote.
   Under a new constitution that took effect in February, the
assembly has greater powers to investigate government actions, and
the president no longer can dissolve the legislature.
</TEXT>
