<DOCNO> AP880423-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Campaign     04-23 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Campaign,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Ponder Faceoff Between Socialist President, Rightist
Premier</HEAD>
<HEAD>With ^BC-France-Election, ran in advance as b0511</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French voters enjoyed a lull Saturday on the eve of
elections expected to determine who eventually faces off with
President Francois Mitterrand, a Socialist acting like a social
institution these days.
   Since the hectic two-week official campaign ended Friday, the
silence has been resounding. No media appearances or campaigning
were allowed on Saturday.
   Even the political grease of voter surveys had run dry. French
law prohibits polls in the week before the elections.
   Even so, voters had plenty to spin their wheels over.
   The confrontation marks the first time in the 30 years of the
Fifth Republic that a president and his own premier have faced one
another in a presidential election.
   All polls predict that Mitterrand, the 71-year-old president
seeking a second seven-year term, will square off in the May 8
runoff with Chirac, France's 55-year-old conservative premier.
   They have ``cohabitated,'' as the French put it, since the
right's victory in parliamentary elections in 1986.
   The main interest in Sunday's voting, then, was reduced to
numbers:
   _ What percentage will Mitterrand win? Will he be able to pick
up enough Communist and centrist votes to expand the 35-37 percent
the polls give him?
   _ What will be the combined totals of Chirac, predicted to gain
22-24 percent, and former center-right premier Raymond Barre, 16-17
percent? That number could give a good idea whether anyone can beat
Mitterrand in the final round of voting.
   Besides Chirac, 68-year-old Barre is the only other candidate
with a whisper of a chance to make it to the runoff. He was long
the top rightist candidate before nose-diving in the polls in the
past two months.
   Barre has said he can't be counted out now. But he pledges to
support Chirac if the premier comes out ahead in first-round
voting. Chirac has vowed to do the same.
   Much also depends on backers of extreme right National Front
leader Jean-Marie Le Pen. Le Pen's strident anti-immigration and
``French first'' appeal has won over an estimated 10-12 percent of
the electorate in an otherwise lackluster campaign.
   Actually, voters will choose from nine candidates Sunday.
Theoretically, it is possible to elect a president in the first
round, but the large number of candidates means that no one can
expect to win the required absolute majority of votes.
   Other candidates in the race are Andre Lajoinie, the official
Communist Party candidate; Pierre Juquin, leader of a splinter
Communist reformist movement; ecologist Antoine Waechter;
Trotskyist Arlette Laguiller; and another Trotskyist, Pierre
Boussel.
   The polls predict Mitterrand will win the runoff no matter who
he faces. He has reshaped his image toward the center in recent
months and has even been dubbed by the French with the avuncular
nickname of ``Tonton.''
   But Chirac was closing the gap when the final surveys were
published a week ago. Moreoever, the undecided vote was high, as
much as 20 percent.
   Many political analysts say Mitterrand must get 35 percent in
the first round in order to win May 8.
   On the right, it was generally thought that the combined
Chirac-Barre vote must total at least 43 percent to give
conservatives a chance in the runoff.
   However, many of Barre's more centrist supporters may abandon
Chirac in the second round.
   The polls open 8 a.m. Sunday and close in most areas at 6 p.m.
In major urban areas, however, they remain open until 8 p.m.
   None of the candidates has come out with a detailed program,
focusing instead on generalities. In his last television speech,
Mitterrand stressed the need for ``solidarity, equality of
opportunity'' and the ``refusal of privileges'' for some people.
   Chirac has responded by accusing Mitterrand of ``proposing
nothing precise for our country.'' He stands on his two-year record
as head of the government, which he says started the country on the
road back to prosperity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
