<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GeneralHospital     04-23 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-General Hospital,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Past and Present Stars of `General Hospital' Gather for 25-Year
Bash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five years of romance, turmoil,
romance, treachery, romance, mystery and more romance were toasted
by past and present stars of ``General Hospital'' at a black-tie
gala befitting the top-rated daytime drama.
   The ABC soap, which debuted April 1, 1963, placed No. 1 again in
the most recent Nielsen ratings, but one of its original stars,
speaking at Friday night's party at the Ambassador Hotel, recalled
its humble beginnings.
   ``When we started, I didn't think we were going to last 25
minutes let alone 25 years. It was very iffy,'' said Emily
McLaughlin, who as nurse Jessie Brewer is one of two original cast
members still with the show. ``We hit No. 1 in 1968, and then we
went down so far we were almost canceled.''
   ``We had a wonderful time,'' recalled actor Jack Betts, who was
on ``General Hospital'' during its first three years. ``(Actor)
Johnny Beradino had been a ball player and had never done a soap
before. Nor had I. We never thought it would last, and John kept
saying he'd have to go back and play baseball again.''
   Betts' character was written out of the show when he was sent to
South America to do medical research and never came back.
   ``General Hospital'' has been consistently first in the daytime
ratings, although it's locked in a tight race with CBS' ``The Young
and the Restless.'' The show has been a huge success throughout the
1980s.
   Nevertheless, ``General Hospital'' was on the brink of
cancellation 10 years ago, before Gloria Monty became executive
producer and turned the show around.
   The show became a pop phenomenon, led by anti-hero Luke and the
headstrong Laura, a tainted Romeo and Juliet involved in murder,
rape and other shady activities. Their wedding in 1981 sent the
ratings jumping off the chart, with Elizabeth Taylor as a guest
star for the wedding sequence.
   Although Tony Geary and Genie Francis, who played the lovers,
have left, there are enough plot twists and offbeat characters to
keep the audience happy.
   Gloria Monty has also left and been replaced by Wes Kenney.
   Beradino, as Dr. Steve Hardy, and Ms. McLaughlin have been with
the show since the beginning. Rachel Ames as the oft-married Audrey
Hardy, who finally settled down with her longtime love, joined soon
afterward.
   Former stars include actors who built careers on prime time,
like John Stamos, David Groh, Daniel J. Travanti, Emma Samms,
Richard Dean Anderson and Douglas Sheehan, as well as film stars
Mark Hamill and Demi Moore. TV personalities Mary Ann Mobley and
Richard Simmons also have appeared on the show.
   Besides Taylor, guest stars have included Milton Berle, Sammy
Davis Jr., June Lockhart, Shaun Cassidy, and three members of
baseball's New York Mets, Howard Johnson, Roger McDowell and Clint
Hurdle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
