<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CapitolDisturbance     04-23 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol Disturbance,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Vendors Create Disturbance In Hawaii's Capitol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE DUNFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emotions boiled over with violence as vendors
failed to stop state lawmakers from selecting the place where the
vendors work as the site for a convention center.
   Several scuffles broke out as about 100 vendors, mostly
immigrants from Korea, surged from a Capitol meeting room, trying
to confront the lawmakers who were quickly escorted out by security
officers.
   Ten Honolulu police officers were dispatched to help a dozen
security officers quiet the crowd in the Capitol late Friday night.
   One Korean woman collapsed, apparently from emotion.
   ``No, No, No,'' went up the shouts as Senate Transportation
Committee Chairman Milton Holt and House Tourism Committee Chairman
Romy Cachola announced agreement on the International Market Place
in Waikiki as site for the convention center.
   Some called the lawmakers ``traitors,'' while others made death
threats. Women wailed and sobbed uncontrollably as others grabbed
and restrained several young men who attempted to chase the
lawmakers.
   Tension had been building throughout the evening as the House
and Senate conferees exchanged proposals and then recessed for
lengthy periods.
   Vendors have been staging rallies at the Capitol since February
and have attended every hearing to testify on the convention center
issue.
   ``I've been here 18 years and we've had all kinds of people here
as lobbyists, but this is the first time I went through this kind
of experience,'' said House Speaker Daniel Kihano.
   ``I just hope they (vendors) understand that the people who
intend to develop the market place are putting up a lot of money to
take care of their problems, to relocate them,'' said Kihano.
   Won Hee You, who has served as a spokeswoman for the 900
vendors, said they fear the convention center will wipe out years
of work to establish their businesses.
   The measure will allow a private developer to exceed the city's
280-foot height limit on the five-acre parcel and put up three
400-foot hotel and condominium towers.
   In exchange for the additional height, the developer has agreed
to build a 625,000 square-foot convention center facility which
would be turned over to the state. Such a facility would cost the
state $150 million to $200 million to build, according to Cachola.
</TEXT>
