<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SmokingBan 1stLd-Writethru a0599 04-23 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking Ban, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0599,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-Smokers Love Airline Ban, Smokers Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf, ``There were,'' to UPDATE with
confusion over rule, and ADDS 1 graf with additional smoker quote.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NR1, NY30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hard-core smokers fidgeted and chewed their fingernails, or
candy or gum, Saturday at the start of the smoking ban on domestic
airline flights of two hours or less, but non-smokers rejoiced and
even some smokers didn't mind.
   ``It's been well publicized, so people really aren't very
upset,'' said TWA ticket agent Vicki Sharpeta at
Baltimore-Washington International Airport.
   Well, most people weren't upset.
   ``Flying is already stressful enough, and now they're going to
make it worse if they won't let me smoke up there,'' said Lother
Straschnitzki of Sonoma, Calif., waiting for his flight to be
called at San Francisco International Airport. ``It's going to
bother me a lot.''
   The federal ban on smoking on domestic flights of less than two
hours went into effect at 12:01 a.m. EDT Saturday, affecting some
13,600 flights a day or about 80 percent of all domestic flights.
   There were no early reports of violations, which could bring a
fine of up to $1,000. Tampering with a lavatory smoke alarm in
order to sneak a smoke could bring a $2,000 fine.
   But there was confusion. Gloria Mitchell of Philadelphia
described a mixup on her two-hour, six-minute United flight to
Chicago: ``First they said we couldn't smoke and then half-way
though they said we could smoke. We all had a fit, and then lit up
all together.''
   ``We don't want to take away smokers' rights,'' Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., the ban's main Senate supporter, said at a news
conference Saturday at Newark International Airport. ``We're
pro-health.''
   ``We try to appeal to their sense of fairness,'' Lautenberg said
of hard-core smokers. ``There are some folks who are upset about
it, and I apologize to them for it.''
   He said he would seek to extend the smoking ban to all flights
after the new law is reviewed in two years.
   ``I'm thrilled. I'm so happy. I just can't breathe anymore on
these flights,'' United Airlines flight attendant Terry Cale said
in San Francisco. ``I'm afraid to go to the doctor to have my lungs
examined for fear of what they'll find.''
   ``The new rule is a good idea,'' said Elva Witler of Green
Valley, Ariz., at the Los Angeles airport, who began smoking at age
16 but gave it up in 1965. ``I have been on planes where the smell
just permeates the plane.''
   An Eastern representative boarding passengers on a flight from
Washington's National Airport to Boston apologized over the
intercom to smokers. Her ``I'm sorry'' was greeted with a
spontaneous ``We're not'' from about a dozen waiting passengers.
   Ahron Leichtman, national president of Citizens Against Tobacco
Smoke, said from his home at Boca Raton, Fla., that the ban gave
him ``a very positive, upbeat feeling.''
   Some airlines offered substitutes for cigarettes, including hard
candy and a chewing gum designed to lessen withdrawal symptoms. Dr.
Don R. Powell, executive director of the American Institute for
Preventive Medicine, advised smokers to put a rubber band around
the wrist of their smoking hand and snap it whenever a nicotine
urge struck.
   Some smokers joked about the change.
   ``I can last two hours without cigarettes,'' said Kim
Silberberg, awaiting a flight from Seattle-Tacoma International
Airport. ``I can bite my nails.''
   ``I survived,'' said Tom Brand of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., but he
lit up the moment he stepped off a plane at Hartsfield Atlanta
International Airport.
   ``A smoker joked with me today about the smoking regulations,''
said USAir ticket agent Heather McDonald at Albany, N.Y. ``He said
one good thing about them is that he can sit up in the front of the
plane now and get off sooner. He said he won't have to be in the
back of the plane waiting for 20 minutes to get off.''
   And some smokers even favored the ban.
   ``I've been trying to quit,'' Anita Carol Irvin, 36, of
Cincinnati, said while waiting to board a flight home at Richmond
International Airport.
   ``The ban is a good thing. If you can't last two hours without a
cigarette, you need help,'' said David Mutz, a smoker waiting to
board a flight to San Francisco from Seattle-Tacoma International
Airport.
   ``It's fine with me,'' said Betty Lockhart of Lompoc, Calif.,
who described herself between puffs at Newark International Airport
as a lifetime smoker. ``You can stand on your head for an hour if
you have to.''
   ``They're forcing me to do something I've been procrastinating
about. So I'm keeping a positive attitude,'' said Bob Wynn, a
smoker from Highland Mills, N.Y., who hopes the ban helps him kick
the habit.
</TEXT>
