<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NevadaRepublicans     04-23 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nevada Republicans,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Wins His First Delegates Since Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson
picked up 14 delegates at the Nevada Republican Convention on
Saturday, his biggest one-day showing so far and his first delegate
gain since Super Tuesday.
   Vice President George Bush won four delegates and another two
were elected as uncommitted.
   The state convention was dominated by Robertson forces who
sought conciliation rather than confrontation with supporters of
Bush, the all but certain winner of the Republican presidential
nomination.
   Support for Bush at this point ``is very wise,'' Robertson said
at a news conference as the convention opened.
   Republican National Committee Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf, who was
elected as an uncommitted delegate from his home state, said
Saturday he met briefly with Robertson to talk about holding
``unity meetings'' that will involve all the GOP presidential
candidates, and Robertson supported the plan.
   Fahrenkopf also said the Robertson supporters are vital to GOP
efforts this year, especially in Southern states that have been
solidly Democratic, and will be a boon because of their eagerness
``to get involved at the grass roots level.''
   Rich Bond, Bush's deputy campaign manager who also was at the
convention, said the Robertson backers ``can have a very beneficial
effect in the party if we all merge. And that's our desire.''
   But Bond also said some antipathy still exists between Bush
supporters and the Robertson camp because ``passions were high,
words were spoken'' earlier in the campaign.
   He added that the Bush camp is prepared to smooth over those
``rough spots'' and work with Robertson to ensure he has a voice in
the GOP. Robertson said he now wants to be a ``rallying point for
conservatives.''
   The overwhelming Robertson victory in Nevada included the
election of his Nevada campaign strategist, Steve Wark of Las
Vegas, as state GOP chairman.
   The Nevada convention boosted Robertson's national delegate
total to 31, while Bush now has 1,081 delegates to the Republican
National Convention, according to The Associated Press delegate
count.
   That put Bush just 58 delegates shy of the 1,139 needed to win
the GOP presidential nomination.
   While Robertson did well in Nevada, he said Republican unity is
what's needed now and that for him, the 1988 race was over.
   Robertson got repeated applause Friday when he addressed the
convention, which at times took on a church-revival atmosphere as
some delegates, their eyes closed and hands raised, prayed aloud.
   The convention, whose 600 delegates included more than 400
Robertson backers, also began singing ``God Bless America'' at the
end of Robertson's speech.
   Robertson, who has ceased active campaigning, marked his last
delegate gain on March 8, when he won five in Arkansas, two in
Massachusetts and two in Mississippi. He won another eight
delegates at a stormy state convention in Michigan in January.
</TEXT>
