<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 1808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WilliamsTakeover     04-23 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Williams Takeover,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protest in Second Day at Liberal Arts School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters joined in singing ``We
Shall Overcome'' and offered advice Saturday to minority students
who occupied a building at Williams College for a second day to
protest racial policies at the school.
   Parents' Weekend is under way at the 2,000-student liberal-arts
college.
   An afternoon rally outside Jenness House, where the occupation
was taking place, drew about 80 people including parents and
faculty. The crowd, predominately white, sang the civil rights
movement anthem and listened to about 40 minutes of speeches by the
protesters, said college news director Ellen Berek.
   Kevin Hinton, 21, a junior from Little Rock, Ark., was among the
protesters who came out of the building to address the crowd.
   ``Our efforts are part of efforts initiated four years ago to
raise concerns about the presence of minority faculty here,
minority concerns in the curriculum and minority students at the
school,'' Hinton, who is black, said in an interview.
   ``There's a very strong sense of frustration, a sense of
inertia. There's certainly sympathy, but over the years the school
has failed to take forceful steps,'' he said.
   Minorities make up a record 28 percent of the 1,207 students
just accepted for the fall incoming freshman class, Ms. Berek said.
At present, members of minorities make up 13 percent of the student
body and 10 percent of the 278-teacher faculty.
   About 30 students stayed in the building overnight; an
additional 30 or 40 came in and out during the day, Hinton said.
   Parents visiting the occupied building included veterans of the
civil rights movement who shared advice on how students should
conduct themselves.
   White students were not allowed among the protesters, who
include Hispanic Americans and students from Polynesia, India, the
Caribbean and Asia, Hinton said.
   A group calling itself the Committee Against Racist Education
took over the building Friday. The Victorian house has served as a
makeshift dean's office during renovation of the main
administration building.
   School administrators intend to run the school as usual, working
out of different offices and continuing to hold talks with the
protesters, Ms. Berek said.
   College President Francis C. Oakley has agreed to meet Sunday
with the demonstrators.
   The students planned to stay in the building indefinitely, he
said.
</TEXT>
