<HEAD>Israel Reportedly Had Abu Jihad Killed Because He Planned New
Terrorism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel had the Palestine Liberation
Organization's No. 2 leader assassinated last week because he
planned new terrorist attacks on Israel and its allies, including
the United States, a magazine reported Saturday.
   U.S. News & World Report, quoting Jerusalem sources in its May 2
edition, says the decision to assassinate Khalil al-Wazir, also
known as Abu Jihad, despite known risks, was based on more than his
alleged involvement in a recent bus hijacking by the PLO that
resulted in three Israeli deaths.
   Quoting Israeli intelligence reports, the magazine says: ``Abu
Jihad was said to have struck deals with Libya's Moammar Gadhafi
and various East European intelligence agencies to restore the
sophisticated PLO terrorist and combat capability that Israel had
destroyed in the invasion of Lebanon.
   ``The PLO would then launch a major new series of terrorist
attacks against Israel itself and Israeli interests and supporters
in other countries, including the United States,'' the magazine
says.
   Abu Jihad was gunned downed April 16 in his villa in Tunis,
Tunisia.
   U.S. News says some foreign security specialists doubt key
aspects of the Israeli version of the story and Jerusalem's reasons
for revealing it.
   The magazine quotes one Western official as saying: ``It has
self-serving aspects, involves a strange bunch of bedfellows and
doesn't make sense for the PLO at this time.''
   The officials also are skeptical of Abu Jihad's alleged presence
at meetings with leaders he has fought for years, and whether the
Mossad, Israel's intelligence agency, could identify precise
details of plans for joint actions by Arab groups that have battled
one another as fiercely as they have fought the Jewish state,
according to the magazine.
   ``But Israeli sources insist that the reasons for hitting Abu
Jihad _ and striking now _ were compelling,'' U.S. News says.
</TEXT>
