<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ItalyGovernment     04-23 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy Government,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Mita Wins Confidence Vote; Coalition Divided Over Mideast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita won final Parliamentary
approval Saturday for his new government but the five-party
coalition is already embroiled in a dispute over Italy's Middle
East policy.
   After a two-day debate, the Christian Democrat leader won a
confidence vote in the Senate 177-106. The coalition had won a vote
of confidence in the Chamber of Deputies Thursday.
   Both votes were a formality since the coalition has a
comfortable majority in both houses.
   De Mita formed Italy's 48th post-World War II government on
April 13 after a month-long political crisis caused by the
resignation of Premier Giovanni Goria, a fellow Christian Democrat
who served for 7{ months.
   The government is made up of the five parties that have governed
most of the decade _ the dominant Christian Democrats, the
Socialists and the small Republican, Social Democrat and Liberal
parties.
   De Mita has expressed hope his government can last through the
end of the legislative term in 1992, but a dispute developed as he
was winning parliamentary approval.
   It involves Italy's policies toward Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization including the months of violence in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and the April 16
assassination in Tunisia of PLO military chief Khalil Wazir. It is
widely believed Wazir was slain by Israeli commandos.
   Socialist leader Bettino Craxi, a former premier, proposed that
Italy give official recognition to the PLO. The PLO does have a
representative in Italy, but he does not have full diplomatic
status.
   Craxi's suggestion was criticized by the Liberals and
Republicans, the two most conservative parties in the coalition.
   At a news conference Saturday in Naples, Craxi added a new
element to the debate. He suggested the European Economic Community
(Common Market) assume a mandate to administer the Israeli-occupied
territories for a transitional period pending a solution of the
Palestinian problem.
   Craxi said Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip were
oppressed and had the ``right and duty'' to rebel against Israeli
occupation. He said Israel had the right to demand secure frontiers
``but nothing else.''
   The Socialist leader also said the Italian government should
lodge a protest with Israeli if it is confirmed that Italian
airspace was violated by an Israeli Boeing 707 that reportedly
helped direct the commando team that killed Wazir.
   Italian air controllers have reported that an Israeli plane,
which identified itself as a civilian aircraft, passed through
their jurisdictional zone near Sicily the night of the
assassination.
   In his 90-minute speech before the Senate vote, De Mita said the
position of Italian governments on the Arab-Israeli conflict has
always been ``constant, intelligent and active'' and that he would
follow that path. Italy has maintained good relations with both
Israel and the Arab world.
   De Mita called the assassination of Wazir a ``useless crime,
which makes the process of peace more difficult.''
   On domestic issues, De Mita restated his intentions to
streamline political institutions. He has promised to make the
legislative process more efficient and strengthen the executive
branch.
   De Mita's close adviser on institutional reforms, Sen. Roberto
Ruffilli, was assassinated a week ago by Red Brigades terrorists.
</TEXT>
