<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     04-23 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Tours Steel Valley By Boat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MCKEESPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson revisited a Democratic
stronghold Saturday to collect favors on a blue-collar cause he
supported and to tap the working class sentiments he hopes to
represent in the White House.
   ``In the Mon Valley I stood with you, fighting for our children
... fighting for justice. Now, on Tuesday, my friends ... stand
with me,'' Jackson said at the first of three riverside stops in
Monongahela Valley towns that have been staggered by the decline of
steelmaking in the American industry's birthplace.
   In January 1985, after losing the 1984 Democratic presidential
nomination, Jackson appeared in neighboring Duquesne with
unemployed steel workers to fight for the reopening of a giant
ironmaking blast furnace affectionately known as Dorothy Six.
   The furnace and the surrounding Duquesne Works have been closed
by USX Corp. and will be demolished to make way for an industrial
park.
   Jackson, reminded Saturday of the disappointing results of the
fruitless struggle to have the furnace restarted, said, ``It was
the principle ... to try to sustain their faith and their will to
fight back.''
   ``Those workers are fighting against the odds of a government
administration that does not care about their predicament, '' he
said as he campaigned before Tuesday's Pennsylvania primary in
which Jackson is pitted against the current Democratic
front-runner, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Between stops, Jackson and his campaign workers traveled the
Monongahela River on a sightseeing boat, floating past red brick
and aluminum-sided homes between scrap yards, coal piles, rail
sidings, fuel tanks, greening valley walls, churches and war
memorials of the struggling towns of Monongahela, Elizabeth and
McKeesport.
   The Democrats' 12,000-to-2,000 voter registration edge over
Republicans in McKeesport is typical of the grip the party has had
on Allegheny County over the last 50 years. Walter Mondale beat
Ronald Reagan by 88,000 votes in the county in 1984, said
Pittsburgh Democratic Chairman Frank Lucchino.
   Jackson was one of the biggest names to join the fight for
Dorothy Six.
   ``I think he's gone out on a limb to identify himself with that
sort of small and powerless struggle,'' said David Demarest of
Pittsburgh.
   The Carnegie Mellon University English professor and his wife,
Marlene, said they liked Jackson as one who could broaden the
Democratic Party.
   ``If we can't bring blacks into mainstream politics, we're in
trouble,'' he said.
   ``Our campaign is changing the face of America,'' Jackson said.
``Coalitions are coming together that never were involved in
politics before.''
   One such newcomer is Joseph Heckel, 62, of Mars.
   ``Jackson represents humanity. He'd like to build rather than
destroy,'' said Heckel, a World War II Navy veteran who has been to
Nicaragua to help the village of El Cedro rebuild after being
devastated by the U.S.-backed Contras.
   ``Our (foreign) policy is just a disaster, and Jackson is the
only one who represents change,'' Heckel said.
   Demarest favors worker-ownership as a way to revive the area's
manufacturing economy.
   ``The inability of Pittsburgh to do that in steel is kind of a
missing link, and I see Jackson as being able to communicate
strongly on that level,'' Demarest said.
   Jackson said rebuilding roads, bridges and other public
structures would re-employ displaced steel workers.
   ``We're not fighting for welfare, we're fighting for fair
share,'' he said at a park beside USX's closed National Tube Works,
the now silent engine of McKeesport's whimpering economy.
   Jackson salted his three speeches with invocations against dope,
despair and prejudice. He encouraged his listeners to have hope and
to organize behind him Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
