<DOCNO> AP880423-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UnidentifiedHeart     04-23 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unidentified Heart,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sister Supports Use of Brother's Heart Before He Was Identified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of a brain-dead man's heart
for a transplant before he was identified was justified because it
helped save another life, the man's sister said.
   The transplant was criticized Friday by medical ethicists.
   ``I'm happy that at least, even if his body is dead, his heart
is beating in another person,'' said Maria Celsa Torres, 20, sister
of Eleno Ulloa Ramirez, 19. ``I'm also very satisfied with the
explanation that they gave me, the authorities.''
   Ramirez was found unconscious with no identification on a Costa
Mesa street early Tuesday and declared brain dead the next day
after surgery to remove a clot in the brain. Police believe he was
the victim of a blow to the head.
   Before he was identified, doctors at Hoag Memorial Hospital
Presbyterian transplanted his heart into Dr. Norton Humphreys, 58,
a retired Fountain Valley physician suffering from a degenerative
heart disease.
   A nursing supervisor who declined to give her name said Saturday
that Humphreys' condition was listed as critical but stable.
   Ramirez's heart was transplanted under a state law that allows
removal of an organ without the permission of the donor or his
family if police are unable to identify someone after making a
diligent effort for 24 hours.
   His relatives didn't find out his heart was transplanted until
Friday.
   ``I think it was good what they did, taking my brother's
heart,'' Mrs. Torres said Friday. ``They saved another life. Yes,
it is painful for us, but we have to accept the reality of it.''
   Mrs. Torres said she last saw her brother on Monday, and that on
Tuesday, her father, contacted her and said he had been unable to
reach his son.
   A friend who works at the hospital told family members a man on
life support there could be the missing man, and they gave
officials there information on Ramirez.
   Mrs. Torres said that on Friday morning, people she assumed were
police officers in plain clothes, took her to the hospital to
identify her brother's body.
   The use of organs for transplant before the victim was
identified drew some criticism.
   George Annas, a law and ethics professor at Boston University's
Medical School, said the procedure was ``incredible.''
   ``If other people have done it, they haven't talked about it in
the newspaper, that's for sure,'' Annas said.
   John Robertson, an ethics professor at the University of Texas
in Austin and a member of the National Task Force on Organ
Transplantation defended the operation.
   ``First of all, we're dealing with someone who is dead. It's not
like they're harming the person. That body is either going to get
cremated or buried,'' Robertson said. ``I'm not sure there's any
serious abuse if they're complying with applicable law.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880423-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 2032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan-LastEmperor     04-23 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Last Emperor,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Movie `The Last Emperor' Draws Large Audiences in Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Emperor,'' the first movie shot
in communist China to be shown on this Nationalist Chinese island,
opened to large crowds Saturday.
   People formed lines to buy tickets to the movie that won nine
Academy Awards. It is about the life of China's last emperor and
was filmed by an international production company.
   ``It is very touching,'' reporter Huang Wu-lan of the China
Times Express said of the movie that opened in 20 theaters in
Taipei and five other cities.
   She said Italian director Bernardo Bertolucci presented a
Chinese world ``very real and persuasive to the young generation of
Chinese growing up in Taiwan.''
   A vast majority of Taiwan's nearly 20 million people are ethnic
Chinese. The Chinese Nationalist government fled to Taiwan in 1949
after losing a civil war to the communists and has since refused
all official contacts with mainland China.
   Unofficially the policy has been relaxed in recent months.
Taiwanese Chinese can travel to China to visit family members and
many mainland products are now legally sold in Taiwan.
   Last month, the government sanctioned the showing of foreign
films shot on the mainland, but movies made by China still are
forbidden.
   Government spokesman Shaw Yu-ming said the Nationalists allowed
the showing of ``The Last Emperor'' because the movie ``does not
contain the poisonous elements of communism nor violate our
national interests.''
   But Shaw said government censors cut a 30-second jail scene in
which prisoners sing ``Dongfang Hong,'' or ``The East is Red,''
which praises communism.
   ``We don't have to listen to this song,'' Shaw told reporters
Thursday.
   Officials of the Government Information Office, which screens
movies, said a brief scene showing the young emperor flirting in
bed with his empress also was cut.
   ``The Last Emperor'' follows the life of Pu Yi as child emperor
of the Qing Dynasty, later Japan's World War II puppet ruler of
Manchuria, then a prisoner of the communists and finally a
gardener. Pu Yi died in Beijing in 1967.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
