<DOCNO> AP880423-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 2033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WarholAuction 1stLd-Writethru a0623 04-23 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warhol Auction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0623,0776</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Prices for Artist's Collection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 22 grafs to UPDATE with results of afternoon
session, new quotes, total more than $5 million, ADD beneficiary of
auction, picking up 17th graf ``A silver''
^LaserPhotos NY40,80</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS McELROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enthusiastic bidders ran up prices Saturday at
the opening of a 10-day auction of Andy Warhol's personal
collection, paying more than $5 million for the art deco and art
nouveau items that went on the block first.
   ``It's amazing the prices people are paying _ some are going for
10 times the amount estimated,'' said Sotheby's spokesman Matthew
Weigman,
   More than 10,000 items, from paintings, rare art deco furniture,
watches and clocks and photographs of Marilyn Monroe are being put
on the auction block in one of the most extensive sales ever held
by Sotheby's in New York.
   Pieces auctioned Saturday included art nouveau and art deco
furniture, jewelry, lamps and household items.
   The two sessions fetched a total of $5,314,347, more than twice
what Sotheby's expected, said Diana Levitt, a spokeswoman for
Sotheby's auction house.
   ``It was a wonderful day,'' said Levitt, who said the sky-high
prices were attributable ``to some degree (to) the Warhol factor,
but to a great degree the quality and rarity of the objects.''
   Proceeds will benefit the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual
Arts, which will support and award grants to cultural institutions
in the United States and abroad.
   The highest bid was $275,000 by an anonymous private collector
for a wood center table by Charles Rennie Mackintosh, made about
1902. Sotheby's expected the table to sell for $30,000 to $50,000.
   The collection includes more than 60 works, including paintings
by Jasper Johns, Roy Lichtenstein, James Rosenquist and Cy Twombly.
Before Saturday's bidding, Sotheby's had expected the collection to
sell for $10 to $15 million.
   The crowd, estimated by Sotheby's at 2,200, seemed as eclectic
as the collection. Some came to buy specific items and others came
to buy something connected with Andy Warhol.
   One man, Alan Dolleck, came to buy something for himself but was
disappointed: ``The prices are outrageous; they went out of sight.
It's not worth it.''
   Most of the people actually buying were dealers looking for rare
items.
   ``I came to buy some of the art deco vases because it is very
difficult to get them in Europe, but they are too expensive here,''
said Vincenzo Geddes da Filicaia, an antique dealer from Italy.
   ``I could get them cheaper elsewhere, but it is because of the
Andy Warhol name that I cannot afford them.''
   Warhol fans merely wanted something connected with the famed pop
artist, who died last year.
   ``I wanted a very strong piece of jewelry connected with
Warhol,'' said Sheila Tronn Cooper, a theatrical producer and
writer, looking at a piece that would go on sale Sunday. ``I saw
this bracelet and fell in love with it.''
   Cooper also came to buy a graduation present for her son, who
she said was ``an artist somewhat like Warhol, and I thought it
would be nice to get him a graduation gift that had belonged to
Andy.''
   Cooper, who has attended many auctions, decribed Saturday's sale
as one of the most exciting she had been to. ``It's mind
boggling,'' she said. ``There are so many newcomers, its like a
party.''
   Sotheby's distributed a special sheet of advice for first-time
bidders.
   A sharkskin-covered console by Pierre Legrain fetched $209,000,
as did a matching table, both purchased by a foreign dealer.
Sotheby's had estimated winning bids between $40,000 and $60,000
for each piece.
   An ivory inlaid armchair by Ebene De Macassar was sold for
$154,000 to a private collector. Sotheby's expected $40,000 to
$60,000.
   A silver tureen and cover made by Frenchman Jean Puiforcat,
which was bought by a London dealer for $55,000. Sotheby's had
estimated it would go for $10,000 to $15,000.
   A silver, four-piece tea and coffee set, also by Puiforcat, was
sold to a New York dealer for $44,000, while Sotheby's officially
had expected $12,000 to $16,000.
   One of the most unusual purchases, according to Weigman, was a
gold and silver ring by Jean Despres estimated at $1,800 to $2,500
and sold to an anonymous buyer for $28,600.
   The remaining auctions will offer an enormous collection of
wristwatches, Indian rugs, folk art, drawings and prints. Warhol's
collection of American classical and federal furniture, which
Sotheby's called the largest and most important available for
auction in many years, will be sold Tuesday.
</TEXT>
