<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 2043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ServicesTax     04-23 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Services Tax,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bitter Aftertaste Lingers A Year After Services Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after Gov. Bob Martinez signed
one of the more controversial levies in Florida history, lawmakers
are avoiding tax talk because of battles that left many licking
political wounds in an election year.
   One year ago Saturday, Martinez signed a bill initiating a 5
percent tax on service industries ranging from lawn care to law and
from accounting to advertising.
   The tax sparked an outcry from many service groups, and
companies such as Lever Brothers, Procter & Gamble and Nabisco
withdrew local advertising of national brands. The protests
prompted Martinez to reverse himself and lead a successful drive to
repeal the tax and replace it with a sales tax increase.
   But the wear and tear of the tax battle is still evident, and
some say the state merely put off a long-term revenue problem.
   The Legislature, which is three weeks into this year's two-month
regular session, shows signs of burnout after five special sessions
in the last 15 months.
   ``I think the session in terms of actually starting has almost
been delayed by the backup of special sessions and the result of
everything that has happened in the last year,'' said House Speaker
Jon Mills.
   Three of the five sessions concerned the services tax, which had
been heralded as fair because it tapped the state's fastest growing
economic sector and because higher-income people purchase more
services than those with lower incomes.
   Martinez, a self-proclaimed fiscal conservative who does not
face re-election until 1990, still is working to rebuild his
tarnished standing with voters.
   Proponents of the services tax said it would ensure adequate
revenue to provide services to the state's burgeoning population,
and they were outraged when Martinez flip-flopped on the measure
last August.
   The governor also angered Republicans because he pushed for a 1
percentage point increase in sales tax as a replacement instead of
meeting a 1986 campaign pledge to cut $800 million from state
spending.
   In his State of the State address earlier this month, Martinez
promised to veto any tax bill sent to his desk this year.
   ``The governor has not intentions of supporting the services tax
again,'' press secretary Jon Peck said.
   But some legislators, including Mills, predict that the
Legislature is likely to consider another services tax eventually.
   The boost in the sales tax to 6 percent, which took effect Feb.
1, is projected to raise $1 billion this year, just as the services
tax was expected to do.
   But economists say the services tax would produce more revenue
over time as the state's services sector grows, revenue that some
lawmakers believe is badly needed.
   The governor has proposed a $20.3 billion budget for the fiscal
year beginning July 1, up from $18.5 billion this year. Many
Democratics say even that increase would not satisfy the needs of a
growing population _ the state had just over 12 million residents
in 1987 and officials say it is growing by up to 1,000 people a day
_ and correct for previous inadequacies in some programs.
   Martinez and the Legislature must reach a budget compromise by
July 1.
   The governor has proposed increasing fees for such things as
state university tuition, fishing licenses, and environmental
permits.
   Lawmakers have quietly discussed increasing gasoline taxes to
help pay for transportation needs, but no formal proposal has been
launched and Martinez has refused to consider such a plan.
</TEXT>
