<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0594 04-23 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Says He Could Retire Any Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts three grafs with McGrath comments after 16th bgng:
Describing the sanctions... Pick up 17th pvs: In its efforts...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega was
quoted Saturday as saying he could retire any time, but that caving
in to U.S. pressure to resign would have a domino effect on the
rest of Latin America.
   ``Gen. Noriega can go any day, on Aug. 12, Nov. 3, Dec. 19, the
first of January, 1989,'' the armed forces chief and Panama's de
facto ruler said in an interview with the pro-government newspaper
``La Estrella de Panama'' (The Star of Panama). ``The calendar is
open and full of dates.''
   But Noriega gave no indication he is willing to step down soon.
   Noriega, who has been indicted in the United States on drug
trafficking charges he denies, has been head of the 15,000-member
Defense Forces since 1983. His official biography says he is 50
years old, but his high school yearbooks indicate he is 54.
   As he has in the past, Noriega said economic and other pressures
applied by the United States to force his ouster are motivated by
political considerations unrelated to the drug charges against him.
   Although he did not specifically refer to the matter, Noriega
has said previously that U.S. actions are the result of his refusal
to help the Reagan Administration overthrow Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government.
   If he submits to U.S. pressure, the general said, ``It will mean
that like a domino, the destiny of all other Latin American peoples
is marked.''
   ``When a people are not docile to an empire, those people and
their leaders will be made a target of that empire,'' said Noriega.
   Noriega also scoffed at reports that some opposition figures and
the Roman Catholic Church have been secretly trying to negotiate
his resignation with his supporters, including leaders of the major
pro-government political party.
   ``It's too bad they're not talking with Gen. Noriega,'' the
general said, adding that many opposition leaders ``are trying to
ride the wave and gain prestige.''
   ``They all want to be like Monsignor Obando y Bravo, they want
to be like Oscar Arias, Vinicio Cerezo or the secretary of the
Organization of American States,'' he said.
   Obando y Bravo is the Catholic archbishop of Nicaragua who has
mediated talks between that government and rebels Arias and Cerezo
are the presidents of Costa Rica and Guatemala who pushed for those
negotiations.
   Panama's Catholic hierachy called on the Reagan administration
Friday to end its sanctions against Panama and said the country has
suffered enough.
   ``We cannot continue like this,'' the church said in an
eight-page pastoral letter signed by Archbishop Marcos Gregorio
McGrath and the nation's 10 bishops.
   Describing the sanctions as the cause of ``misery and
desperation'' for thousands of Panamanians, the letter said they go
beyond ``any strategy of political pressure and constitute by
themselves a threat to the life of our people.''
   Speaking with reporters on Saturday, McGrath said Panama was
going through ``the pathetic and slow agony of a nation whose
economy is rapidly being destroyed.''
   ``In two or three weeks there will be chaos in this country'' if
the sanctions are not lifted, he said.
   The archbishop called for urgent negotiations to resolve the
crisis. Some talks are being held but ``they are not the really
effective conversations that carry commitment that the nation
needs,'' he said.
   In its efforts to oust Noriega, the Reagan administration has
cut off all military and economic aid to Panama, blocked its assets
in the United States and prohibited any U.S. payments to the
government. Panama uses the U.S. dollar for its currency.
   The sanctions, combined with a lengthy shutdown of the nation's
120 banks and a two-week general strike in March, have brought
Panama's economy to a virtual halt.
   Noriega-backed supporters in the National Assembly voted Feb. 26
to oust President Eric Arturo Delvalle a day after Delvalle tried
to fire Noriega. Delvalle, whom the United States still recognizes
as the country's head of state, has remained in hiding in Panama
since his ouster.
</TEXT>
