<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 2105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-1688Protest     04-23 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-1688 Protest,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>300 Mark 300th Anniversary of Quaker Slavery Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The memory of an anti-slavery protest by
Quakers 300 years ago should stir consciences against modern-day
injustices, a group that marked the event was told Saturday.
   ``I think the real question that we should be asking ourselves
today, especially those of us who are white, is how in the name of
God could it be that it has taken us 300 years to get rid of racism
and we still haven't done it,'' Stephen Cary, chairman of the
American Friends Service Committee, said.
   ``The only thing that I can think of that's encouraging is that
for the past 35 years, we've been gaining on it.''
   Cary spoke to about 300 people at a vacant lot in the city's
Germantown section, which was the site of a house where where
Francis Daniel Pastorius and three other Dutch Quakers in 1688
drafted one of the earliest recorded protests against slavery,
according to The Germantown Protest, the organization that
sponsored the gathering.
   The statement was forwarded to larger Quaker assemblies, which
tabled it. It was not until 1776 that Quakers, who became leaders
of the abolition movement, forbade slaveholding by their members.
In 1780, Pennsylvania became the first state to pass a law phasing
out slavery.
   One speaker told the audience that the German and Dutch Quakers
who authored the statement saw only the beginnings of a rigid form
of slavery.
   ``We think of their protest as a protest against something that
was in place. It was not,,'' said Stephanie Wolf, president of the
Germantown Historical Society and a history professor at the
University of Pennsylvania
   ``It was a brave and courageous thing in a new land with a new
language for them to do.''
   The organizers of the commemoration drew up a petition called
``1988 Germantown Protest,'' which said, ``Our Germantown forbears
would have us stand today with the homeless, the hungry, the
unemployed and the neglected.''
   Robert Simpkins, a retired tax assessor, said the need for
protests still existed.
   ``Today, the idea of slavery of men doesn't exist, but the
shortcomings of life such as a lack of decent housing, waste of
youth and other areas where the quality of life is wanting,''
Simpkins said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880423-0146 </DOCNO>
