<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Local Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas assassinated two mayors in
mountainous Arequipa state, officials said Saturday, bringing to
five the number of Peruvian mayors slain by Maoist insurgents in
the past three weeks.
   Andres Neyra of Choco and Daniel Lopez of Ayo were killed Friday
by members of the Shining Path rebel group, said Fernan Fernandez,
an Arequipa municipal official.
   Fernandez said the victims were slain in their homes by the
guerrillas, but he said other details were unavailable.
   Choco and Ayo are hamlets in the province of Castilla, 118 miles
northeast of the state capital.
   The government says more than 10,000 people have been killed
since the Maoist Shining Path began its violent campaign to
overthrow the government eight years ago.
   Officials said previously that rebels on Friday shot to death
the mayor of Socabaya, 545 miles southeast of Lima. On Thursday,
gunmen killed the mayor of the Macachacra, 210 miles southeast of
the capital.
   On April 13, the mayor of Andajes and four other local officials
were slain in the town 75 miles north of Lima.
</TEXT>
