<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0625,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wet Over Much Of Eastern Third Of Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede and 1th graf ``Six children'' to UPDATE with nine
hurt by lightning</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms developed Saturday over the South, with wet
weather scattered over the rest of the eastern half of the nation,
and lightning injured nine people during heavy rain in southern
California.
   Large hail fell in Mississippi, with ice chunks the size of
nickels at Lauderdale, as big as quarters in western Kemper County
and as big as golf balls at Bailey.
   Jackson, Miss., got 2.03 inches of rain in the six hours up to 2
p.m. EDT.
   Alabama also got hail as big as dimes at Selma, Marion and
Demopolis, the size of nickels at York and the diameter of quarters
at Cuba.
   High wind during thunderstorms downed power lines at Prattville,
Ala., the National Weather Service said.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed along a cold front
pushing through the Ohio Valley and the lower Mississippi Valley,
extending from southern Arkansas into southern Indiana and western
Kentucky.
   The cold front created a sharp contrast in temperatures across
Michigan. Temperatures across much of the state were in the 30s but
approached 80 degrees in the southeastern corner.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms extended from Maryland to New
York during the afternoon.
   Showers also produced rain and snow over much of the upper Great
Lakes, and Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., got 3 inches of snow during the
six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Locally heavy rain fell on southern California, with heavy snow
at higher elevations.
   Eight girls and one adult were injured by lightning when they
huddled under a tree at a softball field to escape a sudden
downpour near Tustin. They were taken to local hospitals where
officials said their injuries ranged from minor to moderate.
   Rain fell at a rate of a half-inch an hour in the lower
mountains of Los Angeles County and water overflowed curbs on some
downtown Los Angeles streets.
   Elsewhere in southern California, heavy snow fell in the Frazier
Mountain area of Ventura County and snow advisories were issued for
elevations above 5,000 feet, the weather service said. Two inches
of snow was reported on Mount Wilson in the San Gabriel Mountains
and Pine Mountain in Kern County.
   Farther north, showers extended across Washington state into
western Montana
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 100 at McAllen, Texas. The low for the day was 11 degrees
at Chadron, Neb.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from central
Oklahoma and eastern Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast into
northern Florida, with thunderstorms most likely over the Carolinas
and the central Gulf Coast states.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms were forecast over the lower
Great Lakes region and the middle and northern Atlantic Coast, with
rain likely in the northern Atlantic Coast region. Scattered
showers were forecast from the northern Pacific Coast to the
central Rockies and the northern high Plains. A few showers were
forecast over the north-central states.
   Highs in the 40s were predicted in Upper Michigan and northern
Maine; in the 50s from Washington and northern Oregon through the
northern and central Rockies to New England; in the 70s from the
southern half of California through the Rio Grande Valley to the
middle Atlantic Coast; and in the 80s from south-central Texas to
the southern Atlantic Coast, and in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
