<DOCNO> AP880423-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 2325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ElevatorExplosion 3rdLd-Writethru a0655 04-23 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elevator Explosion, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0655,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Recover Last of Five Killed in Elevator Explosions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf ``The three'' with 1 graf and last 2 grafs with
4 grafs to UPDATE with bodies identified, quote from fire official
on cause.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers searching through the rubble
of a grain elevator Saturday found the bodies of the last of five
people killed in an explosion a day earlier, police said.
   Three bodies were discovered within half an hour of each other
late Saturday afternoon by rescue workers digging through debris,
corn and soybeans in the basement of the elevator, said police
detective Alan Horvath.
   ``There were five people unaccounted for and we have recovered
all five,'' said Joliet Police Captain James Grace.
   The three victims apparently had been in an office area of the
elevator when it exploded and were found under ``a whole roomful of
grain,'' Grace said.
   Authorities at first believed that another person had been blown
into the river from a barge by the force of the explosion, but
Grace said they no longer believe that report.
   He added, however, that rescue workers are continuing their
search in the area ``just as a precaution.''
   Two bodies were recovered Friday after the two explosions
flattened four solos and an office building at the ADM Growmark
granary, about 40 miles southwest of Chicago.
   ``This is just one of those tragic things that should never
happen,'' said Dan Stewart, whose 20-year-old son, Mark, was killed
in Friday's explosions.
   ``He was a good son, and I loved him,'' said Stewart, a farmer
from Anchor, Ill., whose son had been a trainee at the site as part
of a program at Joliet Junior College.
   The tragedy was especially horrifying for the family of Dale
Brent Slatton, 28, of Newark, Ill., whose younger brother was
killed in a car accident 10 months ago.
   ``It's totally devastating to have three sons and to lose two,''
said the victim's mother, Carol. ``To lose any is a tragedy. ...
Now, this is something we have to go through again.''
   After toiling overnight, workers using bulldozers and cranes had
cleared about 50 percent of the debris strewn over the site by the
explosions, said an official at the Joliet Police command post at
the site who would not identify himself.
   Authorities suspect grain dust may have caused the first
explosion, which apparently ruptured a natural gas main about 11
a.m. and touched off a second blast moments later, said Joliet Fire
Chief George Plese.
   But Plese said Saturday that the exact cause would be hard to
determine.
   ``We have no idea what caused the explosions ... and due to that
much destruction it will be very hard to try to pinpoint anything,
but we're going to try to make that attempt,'' he said.
   The bodies recovered Saturday were identified as those of Donald
E. Zack of Joliet, Daniel McLaughlin, 18, of Manhattan and Michael
Dupuis, 23, of Bourbonnais, said Will County Deputy Coroner William
Ferguson.
   David Munchalfen, a security guard, said there had been four
silos at the site, and only a sheet-metal covered grain dryer
remained standing. One of the silos crushed an adjacent one-story
office building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
