<1ST_LINE>d a AM-WorldMonitor     04-23 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Monitor,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Science Monitor Launches New Monthly Magazine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just a week after announcing plans for a half-hour
nightly news program, the Christian Science Monitor says it will
publish a new monthly magazine, ``World Monitor.''
   The first issue of the glossy, four-color monthly will appear in
September, at the same time the TV show begins. The magazine will
include articles on world news, politics, the arts, economics,
culture and personalities with what is described as a ``global
focus.''
   ``We're hoping to throw a life preserver to people who are
drowning in a tidal wave of facts, info, dis-info and mis-info,''
said ``World Monitor'' Editor in Chief Earl Foell, who is also
editor of the Christian Science Monitor, flagship of the Christian
Science Publishing Society.
   Gary Thompson, associate publisher of ``World Monitor,'' said
marketing studies found there was a demand for the ``big-picture''
journalism that both the television show and magazine will offer.
   ``We saw that the newsweekly concept was being covered well but
that many people wanted more than headline type news,'' said
Thompson.
   In addition to the newspaper, magazine and TV show, the
Christian Science Monitor also offers radio news programming and a
worldwide radio shortwave radio system.
   Thompson said Monitor executives hope to make a profit with the
magazine, which will have a newsstand price of $2.50. The Christian
Science Monitor newspaper, with a circulation of about 200,000, has
lost money for years.
</TEXT>
