<HEAD>`The Mole' Wants Job With Rescue Team</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-L'Ambiance Anniversary Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the men who crawled beneath
crushed cement to search for survivors in the collapse of the
L'Ambiance Plaza building now is looking for a job on a rescue team.
   Tony Tufaro, nicknamed ``the Mole'' during the nine-day rescue
attempt that began April 23, 1987, was one of the short, wiry men
who tied ropes around themselves, crawled under the ruins and
searched in vain for survivors.
   Twenty-eight men were killed in the collapse; 14 were injured.
   Tufaro has a scrapbook full of newspaper clippings about his
rescue efforts, but he doesn't have what he wants most _ a job with
a rescue team.
   Tufaro, 25, completed a course in firefighter training in
November at the Southeast Florida Academy of Fire Science, paid for
by a $1,200 donation from a Bridgeport bank.
   He works as a carpenter, the kind of job he held before the
collapse.
   He has contacted an aide to Gov. William A. O'Neill to ask when
the state will set up a disaster response team. He said he was told
that thg team will be set up when funds are available.
   Tufaro said the L'Ambiance tragedy enabled him to discover what
he wants to do with his life, but he said he is frustrated because
he can't find a job.
