<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TurnpikeExpolsives     04-23 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turnpike Expolsives,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Files 12-Count Indictment Against Man Arrested on
Turnpike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese man who is a suspected terrorist
was indicted Friday for allegedly carrying pipe bombs on the New
Jersey Turnpike, officials said.
   Yu Kikumura, 35, was charged with three counts of interstate
transport of explosive devices, three counts of possessing
unregistered explosive devices and three of possession of
explosives by an illegal alien, U.S. Attorney Samuel Alito said.
   Kikumura, identified by the Japanese Foreign Ministry as a
suspected member of the terrorist Red Army group, also was charged
with one count each of having an illegal passport, a fradulent visa
and the passport of another person, Alito said.
   The charges together carry a prison term of up to 90 years.
   Kikumura was arrested April 12 at a service area on the turnpike
in Ridgefield after a state trooper found the sophisticated
homemade bombs and falsified papers, authorities said.
   Officials said Kikumura used a passport stolen from a Japanese
hospital worker to obtain a U.S. entry visa. He entered the country
March 8, authorities said.
   Ronald Kuby, who along with William Kunstler is defending
Kikumura, said he found the number of charges incredible.
   ``You've taken a straightforward single offense, multiplied it,
pyramided it until you face a century in jail,'' Kuby said. ``He is
being indicted for what the government thinks he is rather than
what he has done.''
   Kikumura is being held without bail in the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in New York. Arraignment was scheduled April 29.
</TEXT>
