<HEAD>Soviets Accuse Israel of State Terrorism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Nine grafs SUB for last six grafs pvs, grafs 8-13, Many
speakers ... council recently, UPDATING with Japanese asking proof,
vote expected Monday, other detail, and CORRECTING toll to 171
Arabs dead, sted 170. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union on Friday accused Israel
of state terrorism in the assassination of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's military commander.
   ``It is but another example of Israel's cynical contempt for
world public opinion,'' Soviet Ambassador Alexander Belonogov told
the Security Council.
   Belonogov also called the slaying ``another act of the policy of
state terrorism which has long been practiced by Israel.''
   Tunisia, which requested the council meeting, wants Israel
condemned for the assassination of Khalil Wazir at his home in
suburban Tunis last Saturday.
   Tunisian officials and Israeli sources say Israeli commandos
gunned down Wazir, also known as Abu Jihad. Officially, Israel has
neither confirmed nor denied the allegations.
   In a carefully worded statement issued Thursday by the Israeli
mission to the United Nations, the Jewish state denied it
``admitted'' the attack, as Tunisia claimed.
   The Soviets joined a growing list of nations condemning Israel
for the assassination. Most have singled it out by name. A few,
such as Britain and France, have not.
   Japan's ambassador, Hideo Kagami, noted the absence of firm
proof against Israel. Kagami said any condemnation ``must be based
on solid and irrefutable evidence.''
   Many diplomats said they expected United States to veto
Tunisia's resolution, as it has several resolutions on the unrest
considered by the council recently.
   They said the U.S. vote hinged on the wording of the resolution.
A direct condemnation of Israel was sure to be vetoed, but a
general condemnation of political assassination might survive, said
the diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A vote was expected Monday. Dozens of nations have joined the
debate, including many accused of sponsoring terrorism, such as
Libya.
   Many speakers told the council the slaying further hampers the
prospects of a settlement between Israel and Arab neighbors.
   ``The shots in Tunisia are shots against peace in the Middle
East,'' said Yugoslav Ambassador Dragoslav Pejic.
   A number of speakers told Israel that Wazir's death will not end
the Palestinian unrest since Dec. 8 in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip that has left 171 Palestinians and two Israelis dead.
   Wazir, who grew up in the Gaza Strip, was the PLO coordinator
for the uprising.
   The PLO has issued orders for a ``Day of Rage'' in the
Israeli-occupied terrorities Saturday to avenge Wazir, according to
a leaflet circulating in the area.
</TEXT>
