<HEAD>Pyongyang Accuses South Korea Of Firing Across DMZ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Friday accused South Korean soldiers
of firing across the demilitarized zone separating the two enemies
and destroying equipment. South Korea denied the report.
   A report by the North's official Korean Central News Agency,
monitored in Tokyo, said the soldiers fired on a North Korean post
in Changpung, an area northeast of Kaesong City, on Thursday
evening.
   ``The reckless bombardment seriously threatened the safety of
civil policemen of our side on routine duty and destroyed
facilities of the (guard) post,'' the report said. ``It was
entirely due to the patience of our side that the incident did not
expand into an armed conflict between the two sides.''
   South Korean defense officials said they were investigating.
   The North also accused Seoul of setting a fire Sunday that
burned nearly 3,000 acres on Pyongyang's side of the DMZ.
   In Seoul, the U.S.-led United Nations Command rejected the North
Korean charges.
   ``It's a total fabrication,'' said UNC spokesman Billy
Fullerton, adding that checks in the area found no shooting
incidents at that time.
   Shooting is occasionally reported along the DMZ, a strip of
territory dividing communist North from capitalist South. The two
Koreas never signed a formal peace treaty after an armistice ended
the Korean war in 1953.
