<HEAD>James Garner in Satisfactory Condition After Quintuple Bypass
Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor James Garner was conscious and in good
spirits Friday after quintuple bypass heart surgery.
   Garner, who won an Emmy Award for ``The Rockford Files,'' was
listed in satisfactory condition and was allowed visits from family
and friends one day after he underwent five hours of surgery, said
Paula Correia, spokeswoman at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center here.
   The 60-year-old actor is expected to remain in intensive care
through Saturday and probably will be hospitalized for another week
to 10 days, she said.
   Garner, who People magazine once dubbed ``the last real man'' in
America, entered the medical center on Monday for tests.
   Doctors had planned to perform surgery for an aneurysm, or
ballooning, of his aorta, the main artery carrying blood from the
heart. But they decided on the bypass surgery after a series of
tests this week.
   Surgery for the aneurysm will be scheduled later, hospital
officials said.
   Garner, a spokesman in the $30 million ``Beef, Real Food for
Real People'' advertising campaign for the beef industry, blamed
his heart problem on cigarettes.
   ``I went to visit him yesterday. He said he regretted having
smoked for 45 years,'' said Ron Wise, Cedars-Sinai spokesman.
