<FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-88 0720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     04-23 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviets,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir's Office Predicts New Period In Israeli-Soviet Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A secret report prepared by a team of
specialists from Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's office said Israel
is facing a new and improved period in its troubled relations with
the Soviet Union.
   Israel television said it obtained details of the report and
quoted it on Friday as predicting ``a qualitative change'' in
Israeli-Soviet ties.
   The study was completed this week and was based on various
materials pertaining to the Soviet Union, open as well as
classified, and on an analysis of the Kremlin's latest contacts
with the Arab countries and the Palestine Liberation Organization,
the television report said without attribution.
   Officials from Shamir's office were not available for comment.
   The Soviet Union and all East European countries except Romania
broke ties with the Jewish State following the 1967 Middle East
war. In 1986 and 1987, Israel reestablished low-level diplomatic
ties with Poland and Hungary.
   Last July, Moscow sent a consular delegation to Jerusalem, the
first Soviet diplomatic group to visit Israel in 20 years. A
similar Israeli group was expected to travel to Moscow this month,
but its visas have been delayed, according to Foreign Ministry
officials.
   The specialists' report said the Soviets may now make serious
concessions to Israel, including the issue of the emigration of
Soviet Jews, Israel television said but it gave not details.
   Soviet leaders recently permitted increased Jewish emigration,
which reached a 15-month high of 984 in March.
   Dozens of Soviet Jews, including some who have been denied exit
visas, have been allowed to visit relatives in Israel in recent
months. Some Israeli immigrants from the Soviet Union were
permitted to visit their families in the Soviet Union.
   The television broadcast quoted the report as saying the Soviet
Union may change its pattern of contacts with Israel while taking
into account Israel's close ties with the United States.
   According to the broadcast account, the report predicted an
intensive period of Soviet peace-making activity in the Middle East
and said it may result in an official visit of Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze to Israel during his upcoming Mideast trip.
   The study reportedly noted that Moscow is undertaking a
consistent course of restoring friendly relations with Israel while
demanding more diplomatic flexibility from the Arab states.
   The Soviet Union has said the Middle East conflicts should be
resolved by an international conference and the Palestine
Liberation Organization should participate in peace talks.
   Israel is not ready to accept the participation of the PLO,
which it views as a terrorist group. It also has said the Soviets
must restore diplomatic ties and increase Jewish emigration before
playing any major role in peace talks.
   Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, opposes the proposal
for an international conference, which would include the Soviet
Union as one of the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council. Shamir has said Israel could be isolated at such a forum
and forced to make territorial concessions on the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Shamir's political rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, has
said an international conference is the only way to prepare for
peace talks with Israel's Arab neighbors.
   Peres, head of the socialist Labor Party, expressed optimism
Friday about possible Soviet involvement. Asked to comment on talks
by U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz over the last two days
in Moscow, Peres said:
   ``We still don't know the results of the meeting. But there is
one issue from which we may learn something: It's Afganistan. It
was a very severe case of regional conflict and the superpowers
agreed on how to stop it positively.''
   But Shultz could not persuade the Soviets to restore diplomatic
ties with Israel or pledge to increase Jewish emigration, a U.S.
official in Moscow said.
   The harsh tone of official Soviet statements also contrasted
with the reportedly optimistic study conducted by Shamir's office.
   On Friday, the Soviets accused Israel of state terrorism in the
killing of PLO military chief Khalil Wazir last week in Tunisia.
   ``It is but another example of Israel's cynical contempt for the
world public opinion,'' Soviet Ambassador Alexander Belonogov told
the U.N. Security Council. He called the killing ``another act of
the policy of state terrorism which has long been practiced by
Israel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880423-0179 </DOCNO>
