<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill Two Mayors, Burn Textile Factory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas assassinated two governing
party mayors, burned a textile factory and bombed government and
political party offices in rural districts, police reported Friday.
   Most of the attacks were blamed on rebels of the Maoist Shining
Path movement. The government places the death toll at more than
10,000 since the Shining Path began its violent campaign to
overthrow the government eight years ago.
   Police and government officials gave these reports of the latest
violence:
   Rebels on Friday shot to death Isidoro Garcia, the mayor of
Socabaya 545 miles southeast of Lima. The day before, gunmen killed
the mayor of the village Macachacra 210 miles southeast of the
capital.
   About 15 rebels seized the Cerro Alegre textile factory near
Canete, 85 miles south of Lima, before dawn Friday. They forced
more than 20 workers and security guards to flee and then tossed
incendiary bombs into the plant. The fire blazed for six hours,
destroying bails of cotton worth thousands of dollars.
   A car bomb exploded Friday outside an Industry Ministry office
in Chiclayo, 465 miles north of Lima, and a dynamite bomb went off
in front of the headquarters of the governing Aprista Party in
Huaraz 190 miles northeast of Lima.
   No injuries were reported in the bombings and the attack on the
textile factory.
   Police blamed the the pro-Cuba Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement for the bombing in Chiclayo and said about 100 people were
detained for questioning. No arrests were repored in the other
attacks.
</TEXT>
