<HEAD>David Eisenhower Says He And Everyone Else Should Consider
Political Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Eisenhower, who once left notes in the
White House saying ``I will return,'' said Friday that he or one of
his two daughters could follow his famous grandfather's footsteps
into politics.
   ``We're trying to set the stage where we'll be useful in
politics later on or be in a position to help our children become
involved,'' said the 40-year-old Eisenhower, grandson of Dwight D.
Eisenhower and husband of former President Nixon's daughter, Julie.
   Speaking at a regular Tulsa town meeting, Eisenhower said he
might consider a political future ``down the road'' and suggested
that everybody should run for office at some time.
   Eisenhower said in a news conference before his speech that he
believes Nixon has become an elder statesman for the country
because people have placed the Watergate scandal in perspective.
That scandal, which led to Nixon's resignation in 1974, was
responsible for ``cutting the presidency down to size,'' he said.
