<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Iran,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Said to Withdraw Offer to Support Arms Embargo Against Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has reversed its position and told the
United States it would not endorse an international arms embargo
against Iran, according to a published report.
   China's Foreign Ministry informed U.S. Ambassador Winston Lord
of its new stand after American and Iranian naval forces clashed in
the Persian Gulf this week, The New York Times reported in its
Saturday editions.
   In Moscow, meanwhile, the Soviets turned down a renewed request
from Secretary of State George P. Shultz for support of an arms
embargo. Since China and the Soviet Union have veto power on the
United Nations Security Council, either could block a U.S. move for
U.N. sanctions against Iran.
   Last month, the White House said Chinese Foreign Minister Wu
Xuequian told President Reagan his country would go along with an
arms embargo against Iran if a majority of Security Council members
supported it.
   Following the recent clashes in the gulf, however, China
informed the U.S. that it did not see an arms embargo as the way to
bring the war to an end, The Times reported, quoting an
unidentified State Department official.
   On Monday, U.S. forces sank or crippled six Iranian vessels that
challenged them after they destroyed two offshore platforms in
retaliation for the mining of the U.S. frigate Samuel B. Roberts
last week.
</TEXT>
