<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv23-24   04-23 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 23-24,0800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 23-24</NOTE>
<HEAD>High Court Ruling Seen as Ratifying Authority Congress Felt It Had</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court's ruling this past week that
the federal government may tax interest paid on state and local
government bonds was widely seen as ratifying authority Congress
already felt it had.
   But the decision enraged one group of bond issuers who called it
a ``butchery of the constitution'' and threatened ``drastic
remedies if necessary'' to protect tax exemption from further
erosion.
   Others worried the ruling may encourage a revenue-hungry
Congress to find ways to tax interest on such bonds to fill the
gaping budget deficit.
   The ruling had no effect on the tax-exempt status of the
estimated $730 billion in municipal bonds already outstanding nor
on future issues, which are expected to amount to another $100
billion this year alone.
   Bond fund managers reported no significant selling in tax-exempt
funds occurred after the ruling, and expressed confidence that
Congress would never remove tax exemption retroactively anyway.
   But the ruling could have long-range implications for issuers
who have been selling tax-exempt bonds at relatively low rates of
interest for projects such as schools and roads as well as for
investors who accept lower interest for their money because the
payments have not been taxed by the federal government.
   ``We don't take this as an inconsequential ruling,'' said
Randolph C. Arndt, a spokesman for the National League of Cities.
``It is a very big threat to the capacity of state and local
revenue systems.''
   The case was brought by the state of South Carolina, challenging
a law requiring that state and municipal bonds be registered in the
name of the owner if the interest paid is to be exempt from federal
taxation. It cited the 1895 case Pollock vs. Farmers' Loan & Trust
Co. in which the Supreme Court held that interest earned on a state
bond was exempt from federal taxation.
   This past Wednesday, the Supreme Court rejected the challenge.
In writing the majority opinion, Justice William J. Brennan said
that owners of state bonds have no constitutional entitlement
against having to pay federal taxes on the interest earned on the
bonds.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, dissenting from the 7-1 decision,
said the court overruled ``a precedent it has honored for nearly a
hundred years'' and makes state and local government financing
activities partly dependent on ``whether Congress voluntarily
abstains from tapping this permissible source of income tax
revenue.''
   Word of the decision initially sent tax-exempt bond prices
lower, but the market quickly bounced back as traders appeared to
conclude that it made no fundamental changes in how Congress viewed
the issue anyway.
   ``Congress has been legislating for some time under the
presumption that the Pollock decision of 1895 was obsolete,'' said
George Friedlander, managing director for municipal bond research
at Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   The chairman of the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee,
Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said Congress has presumed for 20
years that it could enact laws involving the federal tax treatment
of state and local government bonds. He said there was no reason to
believe that the court's latest decision ``will either prompt or
deter future congressional action.''
   The Public Securities Association, a trade group for bond
dealers, said it was ``surprised and disappointed that the Supreme
Court went out of its way'' to state its views on tax exemption.
   The group's president, Heather Ruth, said laws enacted in the
past few years have chipped away at the tax-exempt status of some
municipal bonds.
   Fears that Congress would enact restrictions as part of the 1986
tax law prompted issuers to sell a record $220 billion in new
long-term municipal bonds in 1985. New-issue volume has since
fallen to $151 billion in 1986 and $105 billion in 1987 and is
expected to fall to $100 billion this year, she said.
   Alan Beals, the executive director of the National League of
Cities, said local government officials have been ``angered and
disgusted by the unrelenting assault'' by Congress and the
executive branch on local revenue systems and was ``even more
outraged at the willingness of the judicial branch to condone and
even encourage such activities.''
   ``We do not accept this butchery of the constitution and we are
prepared to respond with drastic remedies if necessary,'' he said.
   Arndt said that among the remedies are the possibility of
amending the constitution, enacting legislation to spell out the
exemption or making the issue fundamental to support or opposition
for political candidates.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 23-24</NOTE>
