<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     04-23 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Durable Goods Orders Remain Strong</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite lower-than-expected orders to U.S. factories in March,
analysts say the economy remains strong.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that orders for durable
goods, items expected to last at least three years, were virtually
unchanged last month, reflecting a drop in military hardware that
offset gains in other areas.
   That was far less than the 1.3 percent advance most economists
were expecting. However, the government raised its estimate of new
orders in February. The revised report shows a 0.1 percent gain for
the month, rather than the previously reported 1.1 percent drop.
   The net result was a relatively strong level of orders through
the first quarter of this year, 7.9 percent above a year ago when
compared March to March.
   Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist of the National Association of
Manufacturers, said the report indicated ``modest growth in the
economy, not a boom but no signs of a big dip.''
   Roger Brinner, an economist with Data Resources Inc., a
Lexington, Mass., forecasting firm, said it was premature to worry
about sluggish growth in new orders because shipments remain strong
and the backlog in unfilled orders remains high.
   But the lower-than-expected results for March, along with a
stronger dollar overseas, helped both the bond and stock markets,
which have been depressed over fears of inflation and higher
interest rates.
   The key 30-year Treasury bond's price rose about $5 per $1,000
in face amount Friday and its yield fell back under 9 percent. On
Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 27.69 points to
2,015.09.
</TEXT>
