<1ST_LINE>d f PM-SmokingBan     04-23 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smoking Ban,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Smoking Ban Takes Effect</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new federal ban on smoking on domestic airline
flights lasting under two hours went into effect at 12:01 a.m. EDT
today.
   The new regulations, which outlaw smoking on flights of less
than two hours, carry stiff fines for violations: up to $1,000 for
smoking and $2,000 for tinkering with lavatory smoke alarms.
   They apply to around 80 percent of all U.S. flights, or an
estimated 13,600 a day.
   Under the new rules, airlines are required to announce to
passengers onboard before takeoff that smoking is prohibited on the
flight, and to keep the ``No Smoking'' indicator lights illuminated
for the duration of affected flights.
   Even if a flight is delayed in the air or on the ground and goes
beyond two hours, smoking will be prohibited if the schedule has it
as lasting two hours or less, according to officials of the Federal
Aviation Administration.
   In addition to the onboard warning, many airlines are making
announcements in the gate area before passengers board the plane.
   Travelers flying United Airlines, the nation's largest carrier,
are being advised individually of the new regulations when they
check in.
   Second-ranked American Airline's flight attendants and ticket
agents have been given special instructions to inform passengers
about which flights will be non-smoking, and boarding passes have
been changed.
   Northwest Airlines, whose tough policy goes beyond the federal
requirements by banning smoking on nearly all its domestic flights,
is handing out candies and mints as well as brochures to
passengers. American is providing cinnamon hard candies suggested
by the American Heart Association and the American Lung Association
as a substitute for cigarettes.
   And Continental Airlines is distributing more than 430,000
pieces of a gum called ``Ban Smoke,'' designed to temporarily
control the urge.
   Airlines say they have briefed their cabin crews on the new
regulations and how to handle potentially defiant smokers. Flight
attendants will tell the rebels that they are in violation of
federal law and advise them of the consequences.
   If a passenger persists in smoking, airlines say they may notify
authorities at the plane's next destination, arrange for the plane
to be met by the police or even divert the aircraft in some cases
involving unruly smokers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
